</div><div class="info-panel__citations info-panel__item"><a href="#tab-citations" class="btn btn--inverse btn--slim" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="View Citations" aria-label="View Citations"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-format_quote"></i></a></div><div class="info-panel__formats info-panel__item"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="Go to purchase options" aria-label="Go to purchase options"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="link-text">Get Access</span></a></div></div></div></div></header><div data-core-nav="header" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-nav-wrapper core-container" aria-label="Article navigation"><div><button aria-controls="article_sections_menu" aria-expanded="false" aria-label="Toggle section navigation menu"><i class="icon-list" aria-hidden="true"></i><span>Contents</span></button><nav id="article_sections_menu" aria-label="Contents" data-core-nav="article"><ul><li><a href="#abstract">Abstract</a></li><li><a href="#core-sec-figures">Figures</a></li><li><a href="#bibliography">References</a></li></ul></nav></div><nav id="article_collateral_menu"><ul class="collateral-pill" data-core-nav="collateral"><li><a href="#core-collateral-info" aria-controls="core-collateral-info" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Information & Authors" title="Information & Authors" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-info"></i><span class="sr-only">Information & Authors</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-metrics" aria-controls="core-collateral-metrics" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Metrics & Citations" title="Metrics & Citations" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-metrics"></i><span class="sr-only">Metrics & Citations</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-controls="core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Get Access" title="Get Access" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="sr-only">Get Access</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-references" aria-controls="core-collateral-references" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="References" title="References" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-references"></i><span class="sr-only">References</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-figures" aria-controls="core-collateral-figures" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Figures" title="Figures" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-photo"></i><span class="sr-only">Figures</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-tables" aria-controls="core-collateral-tables" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Tables" title="Tables" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-table"></i><span class="sr-only">Tables</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-media" aria-controls="core-collateral-media" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Media" title="Media" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-play-circle-filled"></i><span class="sr-only">Media</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-share" aria-controls="core-collateral-share" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Share" title="Share" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-share"></i><span class="sr-only">Share</span></a></li></ul></nav></div></div><div data-core-wrapper="content"><div id="abstracts" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="abstract" property="abstract" typeof="Text" role="doc-abstract"><h2 property="name">Abstract</h2><div role="paragraph">Transcatheter mitral valve replacement (TMVR) is a catheter-based interventional technique for treating mitral valve disease in patients who are at high risk for open mitral valve surgery and with unfavorable anatomy for minimally invasive edge-to-edge transcatheter mitral valve repair. There are several TMVR devices with different anchoring mechanisms, delivered by either transapical or transseptal approaches. Transthoracic echocardiography is the first-line imaging modality used for characterization and quantification of mitral valve disorders. CT is complementary to echocardiography and has several advantages, including high isotropic spatial resolution, good temporal resolution, large field of view, multiplanar reconstruction capabilities, and rapid turnaround time. CT is essential for multiple aspects of preprocedural planning. Accurate and reproducible techniques to prescribe the mitral annulus at CT have been described from which important measurements such as the area, perimeter, trigone-trigone distance, intercommissural distance, and septolateral distance are obtained. The neo-left ventricular outflow tract (LVOT) can be simulated by placing a virtual prosthesis in the CT data to predict the risk of TMVR-induced LVOT obstruction. The anatomy of the landing zone and subvalvular apparatus as well as the relationship of the virtual device to adjacent structures such as the coronary sinus and left circumflex coronary artery can be evaluated. CT also stimulates procedural fluoroscopic angles. CT can be used to evaluate the chest wall for transapical access and the atrial septum for transseptal access. Follow-up CT is useful in identifying complications such as LVOT obstruction, paravalvular leak, pseudoaneurysm, and valve embolization.</div><div role="paragraph"><i>Online supplemental material is available for this article.</i></div><div role="paragraph"><sup>©</sup>RSNA, 2020</div></section></div></div><section id="bodymatter" data-extent="bodymatter" property="articleBody" typeof="Text"><div class="core-container"><section aria-labelledby="denial-block-title" class="denial-block "><h2 id="denial-block-title" class="denial-block__title">Get full access to this article</h2><p class="denial-block__text">View all available purchase options and get full access to this article.</p><div class="denial-block__cta"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span>Get Access</span></a></div><footer class="denial-block__footer"><span>Already a Subscriber? </span><span>Sign in as an </span><a href="/action/showLogin?redirectUri=/doi/10.1148/rg.2020200027">individual</a><span> or via your </span><a href="/action/ssostart?uri=/doi/10.1148/rg.2020200027">institution</a></footer></section></div></section><section id="backmatter" data-extent="backmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="core-sec-figures" data-type="figures"><h2>Figures</h2><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1a" class="graphic" aria-label="Anatomy of the mitral valve and subvalvular apparatus. (a) Short-axis CT image shows the mitral valve leaflets, each with three scallops (anterior mitral leaflet cusps [A1–A3], posterior mitral leaflet cusps [P1–P3]) and commissures (medial commissure [MC] and lateral commissure [LC]). (b) Short-axis three-dimensional (3D)–rendered volumetric CT image shows the mitral annulus from the left atrium. AML = anterior mitral leaflet, blue circle = annulus perimeter, LT = lateral trigone, MT = medical trigone. (c) Three-chamber long-axis 3D-rendered volumetric CT image shows the complex saddle shape (blue curved lines) of the mitral annulus. Red dots = trigones. (d) Two-chamber long-axis CT image shows the subvalvular apparatus. AL = anterolateral papillary muscle, LA = left atrium, PM = posteromedial papillary muscle, arrows = chordae tendinae."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200027/asset/images/large/rg.2020200027.fig1a.jpeg" height="1473" width="1253" aria-labelledby="fig1a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1a</span>. Anatomy of the mitral valve and subvalvular apparatus. <b>(a)</b> Short-axis CT image shows the mitral valve leaflets, each with three scallops (anterior mitral leaflet cusps <i>[A1–A3],</i> posterior mitral leaflet cusps <i>[P1–P3]</i>) and commissures (medial commissure <i>[MC]</i> and lateral commissure <i>[LC]</i>). <b>(b)</b> Short-axis three-dimensional (3D)–rendered volumetric CT image shows the mitral annulus from the left atrium. <i>AML</i> = anterior mitral leaflet, blue circle = annulus perimeter, <i>LT</i> = lateral trigone, <i>MT</i> = medical trigone. <b>(c)</b> Three-chamber long-axis 3D-rendered volumetric CT image shows the complex saddle shape (blue curved lines) of the mitral annulus. Red dots = trigones. <b>(d)</b> Two-chamber long-axis CT image shows the subvalvular apparatus. <i>AL</i> = anterolateral papillary muscle, <i>LA</i> = left atrium, <i>PM</i> = posteromedial papillary muscle, arrows = chordae tendinae.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200027&amp;id=fig1a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1b" class="graphic" aria-label="Anatomy of the mitral valve and subvalvular apparatus. (a) Short-axis CT image shows the mitral valve leaflets, each with three scallops (anterior mitral leaflet cusps [A1–A3], posterior mitral leaflet cusps [P1–P3]) and commissures (medial commissure [MC] and lateral commissure [LC]). (b) Short-axis three-dimensional (3D)–rendered volumetric CT image shows the mitral annulus from the left atrium. AML = anterior mitral leaflet, blue circle = annulus perimeter, LT = lateral trigone, MT = medical trigone. (c) Three-chamber long-axis 3D-rendered volumetric CT image shows the complex saddle shape (blue curved lines) of the mitral annulus. Red dots = trigones. (d) Two-chamber long-axis CT image shows the subvalvular apparatus. AL = anterolateral papillary muscle, LA = left atrium, PM = posteromedial papillary muscle, arrows = chordae tendinae."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200027/asset/images/large/rg.2020200027.fig1b.jpeg" height="1473" width="1160" aria-labelledby="fig1b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1b</span>. Anatomy of the mitral valve and subvalvular apparatus. <b>(a)</b> Short-axis CT image shows the mitral valve leaflets, each with three scallops (anterior mitral leaflet cusps <i>[A1–A3],</i> posterior mitral leaflet cusps <i>[P1–P3]</i>) and commissures (medial commissure <i>[MC]</i> and lateral commissure <i>[LC]</i>). <b>(b)</b> Short-axis three-dimensional (3D)–rendered volumetric CT image shows the mitral annulus from the left atrium. <i>AML</i> = anterior mitral leaflet, blue circle = annulus perimeter, <i>LT</i> = lateral trigone, <i>MT</i> = medical trigone. <b>(c)</b> Three-chamber long-axis 3D-rendered volumetric CT image shows the complex saddle shape (blue curved lines) of the mitral annulus. Red dots = trigones. <b>(d)</b> Two-chamber long-axis CT image shows the subvalvular apparatus. <i>AL</i> = anterolateral papillary muscle, <i>LA</i> = left atrium, <i>PM</i> = posteromedial papillary muscle, arrows = chordae tendinae.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200027&amp;id=fig1b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1c" class="graphic" aria-label="Anatomy of the mitral valve and subvalvular apparatus. (a) Short-axis CT image shows the mitral valve leaflets, each with three scallops (anterior mitral leaflet cusps [A1–A3], posterior mitral leaflet cusps [P1–P3]) and commissures (medial commissure [MC] and lateral commissure [LC]). (b) Short-axis three-dimensional (3D)–rendered volumetric CT image shows the mitral annulus from the left atrium. AML = anterior mitral leaflet, blue circle = annulus perimeter, LT = lateral trigone, MT = medical trigone. (c) Three-chamber long-axis 3D-rendered volumetric CT image shows the complex saddle shape (blue curved lines) of the mitral annulus. Red dots = trigones. (d) Two-chamber long-axis CT image shows the subvalvular apparatus. AL = anterolateral papillary muscle, LA = left atrium, PM = posteromedial papillary muscle, arrows = chordae tendinae."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200027/asset/images/large/rg.2020200027.fig1c.jpeg" height="1473" width="1269" aria-labelledby="fig1c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1c</span>. Anatomy of the mitral valve and subvalvular apparatus. <b>(a)</b> Short-axis CT image shows the mitral valve leaflets, each with three scallops (anterior mitral leaflet cusps <i>[A1–A3],</i> posterior mitral leaflet cusps <i>[P1–P3]</i>) and commissures (medial commissure <i>[MC]</i> and lateral commissure <i>[LC]</i>). <b>(b)</b> Short-axis three-dimensional (3D)–rendered volumetric CT image shows the mitral annulus from the left atrium. <i>AML</i> = anterior mitral leaflet, blue circle = annulus perimeter, <i>LT</i> = lateral trigone, <i>MT</i> = medical trigone. <b>(c)</b> Three-chamber long-axis 3D-rendered volumetric CT image shows the complex saddle shape (blue curved lines) of the mitral annulus. Red dots = trigones. <b>(d)</b> Two-chamber long-axis CT image shows the subvalvular apparatus. <i>AL</i> = anterolateral papillary muscle, <i>LA</i> = left atrium, <i>PM</i> = posteromedial papillary muscle, arrows = chordae tendinae.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200027&amp;id=fig1c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1d" class="graphic" aria-label="Anatomy of the mitral valve and subvalvular apparatus. (a) Short-axis CT image shows the mitral valve leaflets, each with three scallops (anterior mitral leaflet cusps [A1–A3], posterior mitral leaflet cusps [P1–P3]) and commissures (medial commissure [MC] and lateral commissure [LC]). (b) Short-axis three-dimensional (3D)–rendered volumetric CT image shows the mitral annulus from the left atrium. AML = anterior mitral leaflet, blue circle = annulus perimeter, LT = lateral trigone, MT = medical trigone. (c) Three-chamber long-axis 3D-rendered volumetric CT image shows the complex saddle shape (blue curved lines) of the mitral annulus. Red dots = trigones. (d) Two-chamber long-axis CT image shows the subvalvular apparatus. AL = anterolateral papillary muscle, LA = left atrium, PM = posteromedial papillary muscle, arrows = chordae tendinae."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200027/asset/images/large/rg.2020200027.fig1d.jpeg" height="1273" width="1188" aria-labelledby="fig1d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1d</span>. Anatomy of the mitral valve and subvalvular apparatus. <b>(a)</b> Short-axis CT image shows the mitral valve leaflets, each with three scallops (anterior mitral leaflet cusps <i>[A1–A3],</i> posterior mitral leaflet cusps <i>[P1–P3]</i>) and commissures (medial commissure <i>[MC]</i> and lateral commissure <i>[LC]</i>). <b>(b)</b> Short-axis three-dimensional (3D)–rendered volumetric CT image shows the mitral annulus from the left atrium. <i>AML</i> = anterior mitral leaflet, blue circle = annulus perimeter, <i>LT</i> = lateral trigone, <i>MT</i> = medical trigone. <b>(c)</b> Three-chamber long-axis 3D-rendered volumetric CT image shows the complex saddle shape (blue curved lines) of the mitral annulus. Red dots = trigones. <b>(d)</b> Two-chamber long-axis CT image shows the subvalvular apparatus. <i>AL</i> = anterolateral papillary muscle, <i>LA</i> = left atrium, <i>PM</i> = posteromedial papillary muscle, arrows = chordae tendinae.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200027&amp;id=fig1d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig2" class="graphic" aria-label="Schematic illustrations show examples of devices used for TMVR. Over 30 devices of varying shapes and sizes that require various implantation approaches and position placement relative to the annulus are being evaluated for TMVR. (Sapien 3; Edwards Lifesciences, Irvine, Calif; and Caisson; LivaNova, London, England.)"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200027/asset/images/large/rg.2020200027.fig2.jpeg" height="1499" width="2496" aria-labelledby="fig2" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2</span>. Schematic illustrations show examples of devices used for TMVR. Over 30 devices of varying shapes and sizes that require various implantation approaches and position placement relative to the annulus are being evaluated for TMVR. (Sapien 3; Edwards Lifesciences, Irvine, Calif; and Caisson; LivaNova, London, England.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200027&amp;id=fig2">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3a" class="graphic" aria-label="Approaches to TMVR device implantation. Illustrations show that TMVR devices can be implanted either by a transseptal approach (a), which requires central venous access and interatrial septal puncture, or by a transapical approach (b), which requires direct left ventricular apical puncture and placement of a more rigid trochar, allowing larger device profiles. Most dedicated TMVR devices require a transapical implantation approach. The SAPIEN 3 device is typically implanted by a transseptal approach. An open transatrial approach has also been used. AO = aorta, IVC = inferior vena cava, LA = left atrium, PA = pulmonary artery, RA = right atrium, RV = right ventricle."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200027/asset/images/large/rg.2020200027.fig3a.jpeg" height="1675" width="1258" aria-labelledby="fig3a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3a</span>. Approaches to TMVR device implantation. Illustrations show that TMVR devices can be implanted either by a transseptal approach <b>(a)</b>, which requires central venous access and interatrial septal puncture, or by a transapical approach <b>(b)</b>, which requires direct left ventricular apical puncture and placement of a more rigid trochar, allowing larger device profiles. Most dedicated TMVR devices require a transapical implantation approach. The SAPIEN 3 device is typically implanted by a transseptal approach. An open transatrial approach has also been used. <i>AO</i> = aorta, <i>IVC</i> = inferior vena cava, <i>LA</i> = left atrium, <i>PA</i> = pulmonary artery, <i>RA</i> = right atrium, <i>RV</i> = right ventricle.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200027&amp;id=fig3a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3b" class="graphic" aria-label="Approaches to TMVR device implantation. Illustrations show that TMVR devices can be implanted either by a transseptal approach (a), which requires central venous access and interatrial septal puncture, or by a transapical approach (b), which requires direct left ventricular apical puncture and placement of a more rigid trochar, allowing larger device profiles. Most dedicated TMVR devices require a transapical implantation approach. The SAPIEN 3 device is typically implanted by a transseptal approach. An open transatrial approach has also been used. AO = aorta, IVC = inferior vena cava, LA = left atrium, PA = pulmonary artery, RA = right atrium, RV = right ventricle."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200027/asset/images/large/rg.2020200027.fig3b.jpeg" height="1675" width="1192" aria-labelledby="fig3b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3b</span>. Approaches to TMVR device implantation. Illustrations show that TMVR devices can be implanted either by a transseptal approach <b>(a)</b>, which requires central venous access and interatrial septal puncture, or by a transapical approach <b>(b)</b>, which requires direct left ventricular apical puncture and placement of a more rigid trochar, allowing larger device profiles. Most dedicated TMVR devices require a transapical implantation approach. The SAPIEN 3 device is typically implanted by a transseptal approach. An open transatrial approach has also been used. <i>AO</i> = aorta, <i>IVC</i> = inferior vena cava, <i>LA</i> = left atrium, <i>PA</i> = pulmonary artery, <i>RA</i> = right atrium, <i>RV</i> = right ventricle.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200027&amp;id=fig3b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4" class="graphic" aria-label="Three-chamber long-axis 3D-rendered CT images with device illustration overlays show several anchoring mechanisms of TMVR devices: A, annulus capture with leaflet engagement; B, trigone capture with leaflet engagement; C, apical tether; and D, radial force."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200027/asset/images/large/rg.2020200027.fig4.jpeg" height="2095" width="2500" aria-labelledby="fig4" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4</span>. Three-chamber long-axis 3D-rendered CT images with device illustration overlays show several anchoring mechanisms of TMVR devices: <i>A,</i> annulus capture with leaflet engagement; <i>B,</i> trigone capture with leaflet engagement; <i>C</i>, apical tether; and <i>D</i>, radial force.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200027&amp;id=fig4">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5a" class="graphic" aria-label="Shape of mitral annulus. LT = lateral trigone, MT = medial trigone. (a, b) Volumetric CT image obtained in the short axis of the mitral annulus plane (a) and wireframe schematic drawing (b) show the complex 3D shape of the anatomically correct saddle-shaped annulus, which includes the anterior horn. (c) LV short-axis of the mitral annulus plane CT image with the 3D saddle-shaped annulus shows the 2D saddle-shaped annulus. The simplified D-shaped annulus excludes the anterior horn by a virtual line between the trigones, the trigone-trigone (TT) distance. (d–f) Volumetric CT image obtained in the short axis of the mitral annulus plane (d) and wireframe schematic drawing (e) show the 3D D-shaped annulus, which is nearly planar. When projected onto the LV short-axis CT image (f), the two-dimensional D-shaped annulus is created. Note that SL distance is larger in the two-dimensional saddle-shaped annulus than in the two-dimensional D-shaped annulus, the TT and IC distances are identical."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200027/asset/images/large/rg.2020200027.fig5a.jpeg" height="1280" width="1321" aria-labelledby="fig5a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5a</span>. Shape of mitral annulus. <i>LT</i> = lateral trigone, <i>MT</i> = medial trigone. <b>(a, b)</b> Volumetric CT image obtained in the short axis of the mitral annulus plane <b>(a)</b> and wireframe schematic drawing <b>(b)</b> show the complex 3D shape of the anatomically correct saddle-shaped annulus, which includes the anterior horn. <b>(c)</b> LV short-axis of the mitral annulus plane CT image with the 3D saddle-shaped annulus shows the 2D saddle-shaped annulus. The simplified D-shaped annulus excludes the anterior horn by a virtual line between the trigones, the trigone-trigone <i>(TT)</i> distance. <b>(d–f)</b> Volumetric CT image obtained in the short axis of the mitral annulus plane <b>(d)</b> and wireframe schematic drawing <b>(e)</b> show the 3D D-shaped annulus, which is nearly planar. When projected onto the LV short-axis CT image <b>(f)</b>, the two-dimensional D-shaped annulus is created. Note that SL distance is larger in the two-dimensional saddle-shaped annulus than in the two-dimensional D-shaped annulus, the TT and IC distances are identical.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200027&amp;id=fig5a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5b" class="graphic" aria-label="Shape of mitral annulus. LT = lateral trigone, MT = medial trigone. (a, b) Volumetric CT image obtained in the short axis of the mitral annulus plane (a) and wireframe schematic drawing (b) show the complex 3D shape of the anatomically correct saddle-shaped annulus, which includes the anterior horn. (c) LV short-axis of the mitral annulus plane CT image with the 3D saddle-shaped annulus shows the 2D saddle-shaped annulus. The simplified D-shaped annulus excludes the anterior horn by a virtual line between the trigones, the trigone-trigone (TT) distance. (d–f) Volumetric CT image obtained in the short axis of the mitral annulus plane (d) and wireframe schematic drawing (e) show the 3D D-shaped annulus, which is nearly planar. When projected onto the LV short-axis CT image (f), the two-dimensional D-shaped annulus is created. Note that SL distance is larger in the two-dimensional saddle-shaped annulus than in the two-dimensional D-shaped annulus, the TT and IC distances are identical."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200027/asset/images/large/rg.2020200027.fig5b.jpeg" height="1176" width="1840" aria-labelledby="fig5b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5b</span>. Shape of mitral annulus. <i>LT</i> = lateral trigone, <i>MT</i> = medial trigone. <b>(a, b)</b> Volumetric CT image obtained in the short axis of the mitral annulus plane <b>(a)</b> and wireframe schematic drawing <b>(b)</b> show the complex 3D shape of the anatomically correct saddle-shaped annulus, which includes the anterior horn. <b>(c)</b> LV short-axis of the mitral annulus plane CT image with the 3D saddle-shaped annulus shows the 2D saddle-shaped annulus. The simplified D-shaped annulus excludes the anterior horn by a virtual line between the trigones, the trigone-trigone <i>(TT)</i> distance. <b>(d–f)</b> Volumetric CT image obtained in the short axis of the mitral annulus plane <b>(d)</b> and wireframe schematic drawing <b>(e)</b> show the 3D D-shaped annulus, which is nearly planar. When projected onto the LV short-axis CT image <b>(f)</b>, the two-dimensional D-shaped annulus is created. Note that SL distance is larger in the two-dimensional saddle-shaped annulus than in the two-dimensional D-shaped annulus, the TT and IC distances are identical.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200027&amp;id=fig5b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5c" class="graphic" aria-label="Shape of mitral annulus. LT = lateral trigone, MT = medial trigone. (a, b) Volumetric CT image obtained in the short axis of the mitral annulus plane (a) and wireframe schematic drawing (b) show the complex 3D shape of the anatomically correct saddle-shaped annulus, which includes the anterior horn. (c) LV short-axis of the mitral annulus plane CT image with the 3D saddle-shaped annulus shows the 2D saddle-shaped annulus. The simplified D-shaped annulus excludes the anterior horn by a virtual line between the trigones, the trigone-trigone (TT) distance. (d–f) Volumetric CT image obtained in the short axis of the mitral annulus plane (d) and wireframe schematic drawing (e) show the 3D D-shaped annulus, which is nearly planar. When projected onto the LV short-axis CT image (f), the two-dimensional D-shaped annulus is created. Note that SL distance is larger in the two-dimensional saddle-shaped annulus than in the two-dimensional D-shaped annulus, the TT and IC distances are identical."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200027/asset/images/large/rg.2020200027.fig5c.jpeg" height="1280" width="1203" aria-labelledby="fig5c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5c</span>. Shape of mitral annulus. <i>LT</i> = lateral trigone, <i>MT</i> = medial trigone. <b>(a, b)</b> Volumetric CT image obtained in the short axis of the mitral annulus plane <b>(a)</b> and wireframe schematic drawing <b>(b)</b> show the complex 3D shape of the anatomically correct saddle-shaped annulus, which includes the anterior horn. <b>(c)</b> LV short-axis of the mitral annulus plane CT image with the 3D saddle-shaped annulus shows the 2D saddle-shaped annulus. The simplified D-shaped annulus excludes the anterior horn by a virtual line between the trigones, the trigone-trigone <i>(TT)</i> distance. <b>(d–f)</b> Volumetric CT image obtained in the short axis of the mitral annulus plane <b>(d)</b> and wireframe schematic drawing <b>(e)</b> show the 3D D-shaped annulus, which is nearly planar. When projected onto the LV short-axis CT image <b>(f)</b>, the two-dimensional D-shaped annulus is created. Note that SL distance is larger in the two-dimensional saddle-shaped annulus than in the two-dimensional D-shaped annulus, the TT and IC distances are identical.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200027&amp;id=fig5c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5d" class="graphic" aria-label="Shape of mitral annulus. LT = lateral trigone, MT = medial trigone. (a, b) Volumetric CT image obtained in the short axis of the mitral annulus plane (a) and wireframe schematic drawing (b) show the complex 3D shape of the anatomically correct saddle-shaped annulus, which includes the anterior horn. (c) LV short-axis of the mitral annulus plane CT image with the 3D saddle-shaped annulus shows the 2D saddle-shaped annulus. The simplified D-shaped annulus excludes the anterior horn by a virtual line between the trigones, the trigone-trigone (TT) distance. (d–f) Volumetric CT image obtained in the short axis of the mitral annulus plane (d) and wireframe schematic drawing (e) show the 3D D-shaped annulus, which is nearly planar. When projected onto the LV short-axis CT image (f), the two-dimensional D-shaped annulus is created. Note that SL distance is larger in the two-dimensional saddle-shaped annulus than in the two-dimensional D-shaped annulus, the TT and IC distances are identical."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200027/asset/images/large/rg.2020200027.fig5d.jpeg" height="1280" width="1176" aria-labelledby="fig5d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5d</span>. Shape of mitral annulus. <i>LT</i> = lateral trigone, <i>MT</i> = medial trigone. <b>(a, b)</b> Volumetric CT image obtained in the short axis of the mitral annulus plane <b>(a)</b> and wireframe schematic drawing <b>(b)</b> show the complex 3D shape of the anatomically correct saddle-shaped annulus, which includes the anterior horn. <b>(c)</b> LV short-axis of the mitral annulus plane CT image with the 3D saddle-shaped annulus shows the 2D saddle-shaped annulus. The simplified D-shaped annulus excludes the anterior horn by a virtual line between the trigones, the trigone-trigone <i>(TT)</i> distance. <b>(d–f)</b> Volumetric CT image obtained in the short axis of the mitral annulus plane <b>(d)</b> and wireframe schematic drawing <b>(e)</b> show the 3D D-shaped annulus, which is nearly planar. When projected onto the LV short-axis CT image <b>(f)</b>, the two-dimensional D-shaped annulus is created. Note that SL distance is larger in the two-dimensional saddle-shaped annulus than in the two-dimensional D-shaped annulus, the TT and IC distances are identical.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200027&amp;id=fig5d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5e" class="graphic" aria-label="Shape of mitral annulus. LT = lateral trigone, MT = medial trigone. (a, b) Volumetric CT image obtained in the short axis of the mitral annulus plane (a) and wireframe schematic drawing (b) show the complex 3D shape of the anatomically correct saddle-shaped annulus, which includes the anterior horn. (c) LV short-axis of the mitral annulus plane CT image with the 3D saddle-shaped annulus shows the 2D saddle-shaped annulus. The simplified D-shaped annulus excludes the anterior horn by a virtual line between the trigones, the trigone-trigone (TT) distance. (d–f) Volumetric CT image obtained in the short axis of the mitral annulus plane (d) and wireframe schematic drawing (e) show the 3D D-shaped annulus, which is nearly planar. When projected onto the LV short-axis CT image (f), the two-dimensional D-shaped annulus is created. Note that SL distance is larger in the two-dimensional saddle-shaped annulus than in the two-dimensional D-shaped annulus, the TT and IC distances are identical."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200027/asset/images/large/rg.2020200027.fig5e.jpeg" height="1176" width="1910" aria-labelledby="fig5e" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5e</span>. Shape of mitral annulus. <i>LT</i> = lateral trigone, <i>MT</i> = medial trigone. <b>(a, b)</b> Volumetric CT image obtained in the short axis of the mitral annulus plane <b>(a)</b> and wireframe schematic drawing <b>(b)</b> show the complex 3D shape of the anatomically correct saddle-shaped annulus, which includes the anterior horn. <b>(c)</b> LV short-axis of the mitral annulus plane CT image with the 3D saddle-shaped annulus shows the 2D saddle-shaped annulus. The simplified D-shaped annulus excludes the anterior horn by a virtual line between the trigones, the trigone-trigone <i>(TT)</i> distance. <b>(d–f)</b> Volumetric CT image obtained in the short axis of the mitral annulus plane <b>(d)</b> and wireframe schematic drawing <b>(e)</b> show the 3D D-shaped annulus, which is nearly planar. When projected onto the LV short-axis CT image <b>(f)</b>, the two-dimensional D-shaped annulus is created. Note that SL distance is larger in the two-dimensional saddle-shaped annulus than in the two-dimensional D-shaped annulus, the TT and IC distances are identical.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200027&amp;id=fig5e">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5f" class="graphic" aria-label="Shape of mitral annulus. LT = lateral trigone, MT = medial trigone. (a, b) Volumetric CT image obtained in the short axis of the mitral annulus plane (a) and wireframe schematic drawing (b) show the complex 3D shape of the anatomically correct saddle-shaped annulus, which includes the anterior horn. (c) LV short-axis of the mitral annulus plane CT image with the 3D saddle-shaped annulus shows the 2D saddle-shaped annulus. The simplified D-shaped annulus excludes the anterior horn by a virtual line between the trigones, the trigone-trigone (TT) distance. (d–f) Volumetric CT image obtained in the short axis of the mitral annulus plane (d) and wireframe schematic drawing (e) show the 3D D-shaped annulus, which is nearly planar. When projected onto the LV short-axis CT image (f), the two-dimensional D-shaped annulus is created. Note that SL distance is larger in the two-dimensional saddle-shaped annulus than in the two-dimensional D-shaped annulus, the TT and IC distances are identical."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200027/asset/images/large/rg.2020200027.fig5f.jpeg" height="1321" width="1200" aria-labelledby="fig5f" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5f</span>. Shape of mitral annulus. <i>LT</i> = lateral trigone, <i>MT</i> = medial trigone. <b>(a, b)</b> Volumetric CT image obtained in the short axis of the mitral annulus plane <b>(a)</b> and wireframe schematic drawing <b>(b)</b> show the complex 3D shape of the anatomically correct saddle-shaped annulus, which includes the anterior horn. <b>(c)</b> LV short-axis of the mitral annulus plane CT image with the 3D saddle-shaped annulus shows the 2D saddle-shaped annulus. The simplified D-shaped annulus excludes the anterior horn by a virtual line between the trigones, the trigone-trigone <i>(TT)</i> distance. <b>(d–f)</b> Volumetric CT image obtained in the short axis of the mitral annulus plane <b>(d)</b> and wireframe schematic drawing <b>(e)</b> show the 3D D-shaped annulus, which is nearly planar. When projected onto the LV short-axis CT image <b>(f)</b>, the two-dimensional D-shaped annulus is created. Note that SL distance is larger in the two-dimensional saddle-shaped annulus than in the two-dimensional D-shaped annulus, the TT and IC distances are identical.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200027&amp;id=fig5f">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6a" class="graphic" aria-label="Measurement of the mitral annulus. (a) Short-axis CT image obtained at late diastole (left) (typically obtained at the 70%–80% R-R interval) perpendicular to the LV central axis (white dashed curved arrows) and corresponding sections (white straight arrows, right images) demonstrate how the perimeter of the annulus is measured. The plane is rotated around the central axis of the LV, and seed points are placed at the annulus in a long-axis view (right images). Posteriorly, a posterior leaflet insertion site with the annulus is used. Anteriorly, the insertion of the noncoronary and left coronary cusps with the intervalvular fibrosa is used. A cubic spline (green lines, green arrows) is created from these seed points. This represents the 3D perimeter of the saddle-shaped annulus. 4CH = four-chamber view, 3CH = three-chamber view. (b) Drawing (top) shows the trigones, and a virtual trigone-trigone (TT) line is drawn, which excludes the anterior horn to form a 3D D-shaped annulus (blue outlines). The 3D annulus perimeter is projected onto the short-axis CT image (bottom) and represents the two-dimensional D-shaped annulus. The annulus perimeter, area, trigone-trigone distance, IC distance, and SL distance are recorded. LT = lateral trigone, MT = medial trigone. (c) Three-chamber long-axis 3D volumetric CT image shows the angulation between the central axis of the mitral annulus (green dotted line) and central axis of the LV (yellow dotted line). Blue curved lines = annulus outline, red dots = trigones."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200027/asset/images/large/rg.2020200027.fig6a.jpeg" height="2087" width="2073" aria-labelledby="fig6a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6a</span>. Measurement of the mitral annulus. <b>(a)</b> Short-axis CT image obtained at late diastole (left) (typically obtained at the 70%–80% R-R interval) perpendicular to the LV central axis (white dashed curved arrows) and corresponding sections (white straight arrows, right images) demonstrate how the perimeter of the annulus is measured. The plane is rotated around the central axis of the LV, and seed points are placed at the annulus in a long-axis view (right images). Posteriorly, a posterior leaflet insertion site with the annulus is used. Anteriorly, the insertion of the noncoronary and left coronary cusps with the intervalvular fibrosa is used. A cubic spline (green lines, green arrows) is created from these seed points. This represents the 3D perimeter of the saddle-shaped annulus. <i>4CH</i> = four-chamber view, <i>3CH</i> = three-chamber view. <b>(b)</b> Drawing (top) shows the trigones, and a virtual trigone-trigone <i>(TT)</i> line is drawn, which excludes the anterior horn to form a 3D D-shaped annulus (blue outlines). The 3D annulus perimeter is projected onto the short-axis CT image (bottom) and represents the two-dimensional D-shaped annulus. The annulus perimeter, area, trigone-trigone distance, IC distance, and SL distance are recorded. <i>LT</i> = lateral trigone, <i>MT</i> = medial trigone. <b>(c)</b> Three-chamber long-axis 3D volumetric CT image shows the angulation between the central axis of the mitral annulus (green dotted line) and central axis of the LV (yellow dotted line). Blue curved lines = annulus outline, red dots = trigones.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200027&amp;id=fig6a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6b" class="graphic" aria-label="Measurement of the mitral annulus. (a) Short-axis CT image obtained at late diastole (left) (typically obtained at the 70%–80% R-R interval) perpendicular to the LV central axis (white dashed curved arrows) and corresponding sections (white straight arrows, right images) demonstrate how the perimeter of the annulus is measured. The plane is rotated around the central axis of the LV, and seed points are placed at the annulus in a long-axis view (right images). Posteriorly, a posterior leaflet insertion site with the annulus is used. Anteriorly, the insertion of the noncoronary and left coronary cusps with the intervalvular fibrosa is used. A cubic spline (green lines, green arrows) is created from these seed points. This represents the 3D perimeter of the saddle-shaped annulus. 4CH = four-chamber view, 3CH = three-chamber view. (b) Drawing (top) shows the trigones, and a virtual trigone-trigone (TT) line is drawn, which excludes the anterior horn to form a 3D D-shaped annulus (blue outlines). The 3D annulus perimeter is projected onto the short-axis CT image (bottom) and represents the two-dimensional D-shaped annulus. The annulus perimeter, area, trigone-trigone distance, IC distance, and SL distance are recorded. LT = lateral trigone, MT = medial trigone. (c) Three-chamber long-axis 3D volumetric CT image shows the angulation between the central axis of the mitral annulus (green dotted line) and central axis of the LV (yellow dotted line). Blue curved lines = annulus outline, red dots = trigones."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200027/asset/images/large/rg.2020200027.fig6b.jpeg" height="2087" width="1474" aria-labelledby="fig6b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6b</span>. Measurement of the mitral annulus. <b>(a)</b> Short-axis CT image obtained at late diastole (left) (typically obtained at the 70%–80% R-R interval) perpendicular to the LV central axis (white dashed curved arrows) and corresponding sections (white straight arrows, right images) demonstrate how the perimeter of the annulus is measured. The plane is rotated around the central axis of the LV, and seed points are placed at the annulus in a long-axis view (right images). Posteriorly, a posterior leaflet insertion site with the annulus is used. Anteriorly, the insertion of the noncoronary and left coronary cusps with the intervalvular fibrosa is used. A cubic spline (green lines, green arrows) is created from these seed points. This represents the 3D perimeter of the saddle-shaped annulus. <i>4CH</i> = four-chamber view, <i>3CH</i> = three-chamber view. <b>(b)</b> Drawing (top) shows the trigones, and a virtual trigone-trigone <i>(TT)</i> line is drawn, which excludes the anterior horn to form a 3D D-shaped annulus (blue outlines). The 3D annulus perimeter is projected onto the short-axis CT image (bottom) and represents the two-dimensional D-shaped annulus. The annulus perimeter, area, trigone-trigone distance, IC distance, and SL distance are recorded. <i>LT</i> = lateral trigone, <i>MT</i> = medial trigone. <b>(c)</b> Three-chamber long-axis 3D volumetric CT image shows the angulation between the central axis of the mitral annulus (green dotted line) and central axis of the LV (yellow dotted line). Blue curved lines = annulus outline, red dots = trigones.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200027&amp;id=fig6b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6c" class="graphic" aria-label="Measurement of the mitral annulus. (a) Short-axis CT image obtained at late diastole (left) (typically obtained at the 70%–80% R-R interval) perpendicular to the LV central axis (white dashed curved arrows) and corresponding sections (white straight arrows, right images) demonstrate how the perimeter of the annulus is measured. The plane is rotated around the central axis of the LV, and seed points are placed at the annulus in a long-axis view (right images). Posteriorly, a posterior leaflet insertion site with the annulus is used. Anteriorly, the insertion of the noncoronary and left coronary cusps with the intervalvular fibrosa is used. A cubic spline (green lines, green arrows) is created from these seed points. This represents the 3D perimeter of the saddle-shaped annulus. 4CH = four-chamber view, 3CH = three-chamber view. (b) Drawing (top) shows the trigones, and a virtual trigone-trigone (TT) line is drawn, which excludes the anterior horn to form a 3D D-shaped annulus (blue outlines). The 3D annulus perimeter is projected onto the short-axis CT image (bottom) and represents the two-dimensional D-shaped annulus. The annulus perimeter, area, trigone-trigone distance, IC distance, and SL distance are recorded. LT = lateral trigone, MT = medial trigone. (c) Three-chamber long-axis 3D volumetric CT image shows the angulation between the central axis of the mitral annulus (green dotted line) and central axis of the LV (yellow dotted line). Blue curved lines = annulus outline, red dots = trigones."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200027/asset/images/large/rg.2020200027.fig6c.jpeg" height="1682" width="1600" aria-labelledby="fig6c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6c</span>. Measurement of the mitral annulus. <b>(a)</b> Short-axis CT image obtained at late diastole (left) (typically obtained at the 70%–80% R-R interval) perpendicular to the LV central axis (white dashed curved arrows) and corresponding sections (white straight arrows, right images) demonstrate how the perimeter of the annulus is measured. The plane is rotated around the central axis of the LV, and seed points are placed at the annulus in a long-axis view (right images). Posteriorly, a posterior leaflet insertion site with the annulus is used. Anteriorly, the insertion of the noncoronary and left coronary cusps with the intervalvular fibrosa is used. A cubic spline (green lines, green arrows) is created from these seed points. This represents the 3D perimeter of the saddle-shaped annulus. <i>4CH</i> = four-chamber view, <i>3CH</i> = three-chamber view. <b>(b)</b> Drawing (top) shows the trigones, and a virtual trigone-trigone <i>(TT)</i> line is drawn, which excludes the anterior horn to form a 3D D-shaped annulus (blue outlines). The 3D annulus perimeter is projected onto the short-axis CT image (bottom) and represents the two-dimensional D-shaped annulus. The annulus perimeter, area, trigone-trigone distance, IC distance, and SL distance are recorded. <i>LT</i> = lateral trigone, <i>MT</i> = medial trigone. <b>(c)</b> Three-chamber long-axis 3D volumetric CT image shows the angulation between the central axis of the mitral annulus (green dotted line) and central axis of the LV (yellow dotted line). Blue curved lines = annulus outline, red dots = trigones.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200027&amp;id=fig6c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7a" class="graphic" aria-label="LVOT (a, b) and neo-LVOT (c, d) depicted on 3D illustrations (a, c) and three-chamber long-axis CT images with 3D overlays (b, d). The LVOT (yellow area in a and b) is the channel through which blood exits the LV and is defined as the volume between the basal interventricular septum anteriorly and aortomitral continuity posteriorly (a, b). After mitral prosthesis (green area in c, green lines in d) placement, the deflected anterior mitral leaflet elongates and narrows the LVOT, creating the neo-LVOT (purple area in c and d)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200027/asset/images/large/rg.2020200027.fig7a.jpeg" height="1195" width="775" aria-labelledby="fig7a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7a</span>. LVOT <b>(a, b)</b> and neo-LVOT <b>(c, d)</b> depicted on 3D illustrations (<b>a, c</b>) and three-chamber long-axis CT images with 3D overlays (<b>b, d</b>). The LVOT (yellow area in <b>a</b> and <b>b</b>) is the channel through which blood exits the LV and is defined as the volume between the basal interventricular septum anteriorly and aortomitral continuity posteriorly <b>(a, b)</b>. After mitral prosthesis (green area in <b>c</b>, green lines in <b>d</b>) placement, the deflected anterior mitral leaflet elongates and narrows the LVOT, creating the neo-LVOT (purple area in <b>c</b> and <b>d</b>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200027&amp;id=fig7a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7b" class="graphic" aria-label="LVOT (a, b) and neo-LVOT (c, d) depicted on 3D illustrations (a, c) and three-chamber long-axis CT images with 3D overlays (b, d). The LVOT (yellow area in a and b) is the channel through which blood exits the LV and is defined as the volume between the basal interventricular septum anteriorly and aortomitral continuity posteriorly (a, b). After mitral prosthesis (green area in c, green lines in d) placement, the deflected anterior mitral leaflet elongates and narrows the LVOT, creating the neo-LVOT (purple area in c and d)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200027/asset/images/large/rg.2020200027.fig7b.jpeg" height="1195" width="982" aria-labelledby="fig7b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7b</span>. LVOT <b>(a, b)</b> and neo-LVOT <b>(c, d)</b> depicted on 3D illustrations (<b>a, c</b>) and three-chamber long-axis CT images with 3D overlays (<b>b, d</b>). The LVOT (yellow area in <b>a</b> and <b>b</b>) is the channel through which blood exits the LV and is defined as the volume between the basal interventricular septum anteriorly and aortomitral continuity posteriorly <b>(a, b)</b>. After mitral prosthesis (green area in <b>c</b>, green lines in <b>d</b>) placement, the deflected anterior mitral leaflet elongates and narrows the LVOT, creating the neo-LVOT (purple area in <b>c</b> and <b>d</b>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200027&amp;id=fig7b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7c" class="graphic" aria-label="LVOT (a, b) and neo-LVOT (c, d) depicted on 3D illustrations (a, c) and three-chamber long-axis CT images with 3D overlays (b, d). The LVOT (yellow area in a and b) is the channel through which blood exits the LV and is defined as the volume between the basal interventricular septum anteriorly and aortomitral continuity posteriorly (a, b). After mitral prosthesis (green area in c, green lines in d) placement, the deflected anterior mitral leaflet elongates and narrows the LVOT, creating the neo-LVOT (purple area in c and d)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200027/asset/images/large/rg.2020200027.fig7c.jpeg" height="1195" width="784" aria-labelledby="fig7c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7c</span>. LVOT <b>(a, b)</b> and neo-LVOT <b>(c, d)</b> depicted on 3D illustrations (<b>a, c</b>) and three-chamber long-axis CT images with 3D overlays (<b>b, d</b>). The LVOT (yellow area in <b>a</b> and <b>b</b>) is the channel through which blood exits the LV and is defined as the volume between the basal interventricular septum anteriorly and aortomitral continuity posteriorly <b>(a, b)</b>. After mitral prosthesis (green area in <b>c</b>, green lines in <b>d</b>) placement, the deflected anterior mitral leaflet elongates and narrows the LVOT, creating the neo-LVOT (purple area in <b>c</b> and <b>d</b>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200027&amp;id=fig7c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7d" class="graphic" aria-label="LVOT (a, b) and neo-LVOT (c, d) depicted on 3D illustrations (a, c) and three-chamber long-axis CT images with 3D overlays (b, d). The LVOT (yellow area in a and b) is the channel through which blood exits the LV and is defined as the volume between the basal interventricular septum anteriorly and aortomitral continuity posteriorly (a, b). After mitral prosthesis (green area in c, green lines in d) placement, the deflected anterior mitral leaflet elongates and narrows the LVOT, creating the neo-LVOT (purple area in c and d)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200027/asset/images/large/rg.2020200027.fig7d.jpeg" height="1195" width="1112" aria-labelledby="fig7d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7d</span>. LVOT <b>(a, b)</b> and neo-LVOT <b>(c, d)</b> depicted on 3D illustrations (<b>a, c</b>) and three-chamber long-axis CT images with 3D overlays (<b>b, d</b>). The LVOT (yellow area in <b>a</b> and <b>b</b>) is the channel through which blood exits the LV and is defined as the volume between the basal interventricular septum anteriorly and aortomitral continuity posteriorly <b>(a, b)</b>. After mitral prosthesis (green area in <b>c</b>, green lines in <b>d</b>) placement, the deflected anterior mitral leaflet elongates and narrows the LVOT, creating the neo-LVOT (purple area in <b>c</b> and <b>d</b>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200027&amp;id=fig7d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8a" class="graphic" aria-label="Virtual prosthesis simulation. (a) Illustration shows a virtual prosthesis, which is a digital model of a TMVR device that can be used in the CT dataspace to simulate expected device position and, importantly, its effect on the neo-LVOT. Virtual prostheses can be manually created or obtained from vendors. (b) Three-chamber long-axis CT image shows that in the CT dataspace, the virtual prosthesis central axis should align with the mitral annulus central axis. The virtual prosthesis (arrow) is then translated along the mitral annulus central axis until the desired seating position in the annulus is achieved. This position is typically a ventricular-atrial offset of 80:20."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200027/asset/images/large/rg.2020200027.fig8a.jpeg" height="819" width="1700" aria-labelledby="fig8a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8a</span>. Virtual prosthesis simulation. <b>(a)</b> Illustration shows a virtual prosthesis, which is a digital model of a TMVR device that can be used in the CT dataspace to simulate expected device position and, importantly, its effect on the neo-LVOT. Virtual prostheses can be manually created or obtained from vendors. <b>(b)</b> Three-chamber long-axis CT image shows that in the CT dataspace, the virtual prosthesis central axis should align with the mitral annulus central axis. The virtual prosthesis (arrow) is then translated along the mitral annulus central axis until the desired seating position in the annulus is achieved. This position is typically a ventricular-atrial offset of 80:20.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200027&amp;id=fig8a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8b" class="graphic" aria-label="Virtual prosthesis simulation. (a) Illustration shows a virtual prosthesis, which is a digital model of a TMVR device that can be used in the CT dataspace to simulate expected device position and, importantly, its effect on the neo-LVOT. Virtual prostheses can be manually created or obtained from vendors. (b) Three-chamber long-axis CT image shows that in the CT dataspace, the virtual prosthesis central axis should align with the mitral annulus central axis. The virtual prosthesis (arrow) is then translated along the mitral annulus central axis until the desired seating position in the annulus is achieved. This position is typically a ventricular-atrial offset of 80:20."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200027/asset/images/large/rg.2020200027.fig8b.jpeg" height="1597" width="1699" aria-labelledby="fig8b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8b</span>. Virtual prosthesis simulation. <b>(a)</b> Illustration shows a virtual prosthesis, which is a digital model of a TMVR device that can be used in the CT dataspace to simulate expected device position and, importantly, its effect on the neo-LVOT. Virtual prostheses can be manually created or obtained from vendors. <b>(b)</b> Three-chamber long-axis CT image shows that in the CT dataspace, the virtual prosthesis central axis should align with the mitral annulus central axis. The virtual prosthesis (arrow) is then translated along the mitral annulus central axis until the desired seating position in the annulus is achieved. This position is typically a ventricular-atrial offset of 80:20.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200027&amp;id=fig8b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9a" class="graphic" aria-label="Measurement of the neo-LVOT area. (a) Three-chamber (top) and short-axis (bottom) CT images obtained at end systole following virtual prosthesis placement (green outlines in a; green areas in b and c) show curved planar reformations along the neo-LVOT (blue dotted double-sided arrow, blue dot, pink area in the top image) to find the narrowest cross-sectional area (dotted yellow line, pink area in the bottom image), which is then measured in the cross-sectional view (bottom). Neo-LVOT areas greater than or equal to 200 mm2 are often associated with a low risk of TMVR-induced LVOT obstruction. (b, c) Short-axis CT images of the neo-LVOT show small (b) and very small (c) areas (orange area in b, red area in c), measuring 1.3 cm2 and 0.6 cm2, respectively."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200027/asset/images/large/rg.2020200027.fig9a.jpeg" height="2746" width="1229" aria-labelledby="fig9a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9a</span>. Measurement of the neo-LVOT area. <b>(a)</b> Three-chamber (top) and short-axis (bottom) CT images obtained at end systole following virtual prosthesis placement (green outlines in <b>a</b>; green areas in <b>b</b> and <b>c</b>) show curved planar reformations along the neo-LVOT (blue dotted double-sided arrow, blue dot, pink area in the top image) to find the narrowest cross-sectional area (dotted yellow line, pink area in the bottom image), which is then measured in the cross-sectional view (bottom). Neo-LVOT areas greater than or equal to 200 mm<sup>2</sup> are often associated with a low risk of TMVR-induced LVOT obstruction. <b>(b, c)</b> Short-axis CT images of the neo-LVOT show small <b>(b)</b> and very small <b>(c)</b> areas (orange area in <b>b</b>, red area in <b>c</b>), measuring 1.3 cm<sup>2</sup> and 0.6 cm<sup>2</sup>, respectively.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200027&amp;id=fig9a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9b" class="graphic" aria-label="Measurement of the neo-LVOT area. (a) Three-chamber (top) and short-axis (bottom) CT images obtained at end systole following virtual prosthesis placement (green outlines in a; green areas in b and c) show curved planar reformations along the neo-LVOT (blue dotted double-sided arrow, blue dot, pink area in the top image) to find the narrowest cross-sectional area (dotted yellow line, pink area in the bottom image), which is then measured in the cross-sectional view (bottom). Neo-LVOT areas greater than or equal to 200 mm2 are often associated with a low risk of TMVR-induced LVOT obstruction. (b, c) Short-axis CT images of the neo-LVOT show small (b) and very small (c) areas (orange area in b, red area in c), measuring 1.3 cm2 and 0.6 cm2, respectively."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200027/asset/images/large/rg.2020200027.fig9b.jpeg" height="1297" width="1221" aria-labelledby="fig9b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9b</span>. Measurement of the neo-LVOT area. <b>(a)</b> Three-chamber (top) and short-axis (bottom) CT images obtained at end systole following virtual prosthesis placement (green outlines in <b>a</b>; green areas in <b>b</b> and <b>c</b>) show curved planar reformations along the neo-LVOT (blue dotted double-sided arrow, blue dot, pink area in the top image) to find the narrowest cross-sectional area (dotted yellow line, pink area in the bottom image), which is then measured in the cross-sectional view (bottom). Neo-LVOT areas greater than or equal to 200 mm<sup>2</sup> are often associated with a low risk of TMVR-induced LVOT obstruction. <b>(b, c)</b> Short-axis CT images of the neo-LVOT show small <b>(b)</b> and very small <b>(c)</b> areas (orange area in <b>b</b>, red area in <b>c</b>), measuring 1.3 cm<sup>2</sup> and 0.6 cm<sup>2</sup>, respectively.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200027&amp;id=fig9b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9c" class="graphic" aria-label="Measurement of the neo-LVOT area. (a) Three-chamber (top) and short-axis (bottom) CT images obtained at end systole following virtual prosthesis placement (green outlines in a; green areas in b and c) show curved planar reformations along the neo-LVOT (blue dotted double-sided arrow, blue dot, pink area in the top image) to find the narrowest cross-sectional area (dotted yellow line, pink area in the bottom image), which is then measured in the cross-sectional view (bottom). Neo-LVOT areas greater than or equal to 200 mm2 are often associated with a low risk of TMVR-induced LVOT obstruction. (b, c) Short-axis CT images of the neo-LVOT show small (b) and very small (c) areas (orange area in b, red area in c), measuring 1.3 cm2 and 0.6 cm2, respectively."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200027/asset/images/large/rg.2020200027.fig9c.jpeg" height="1299" width="1221" aria-labelledby="fig9c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9c</span>. Measurement of the neo-LVOT area. <b>(a)</b> Three-chamber (top) and short-axis (bottom) CT images obtained at end systole following virtual prosthesis placement (green outlines in <b>a</b>; green areas in <b>b</b> and <b>c</b>) show curved planar reformations along the neo-LVOT (blue dotted double-sided arrow, blue dot, pink area in the top image) to find the narrowest cross-sectional area (dotted yellow line, pink area in the bottom image), which is then measured in the cross-sectional view (bottom). Neo-LVOT areas greater than or equal to 200 mm<sup>2</sup> are often associated with a low risk of TMVR-induced LVOT obstruction. <b>(b, c)</b> Short-axis CT images of the neo-LVOT show small <b>(b)</b> and very small <b>(c)</b> areas (orange area in <b>b</b>, red area in <b>c</b>), measuring 1.3 cm<sup>2</sup> and 0.6 cm<sup>2</sup>, respectively.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200027&amp;id=fig9c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10" class="graphic" aria-label="Device-specific characteristics affecting neo-LVOT size. Device flaring illustrations (top) show outward angulation (double-sided arrows) of the ventricular side of the prosthesis (green areas). The greater the device flaring, the higher the LVOT obstruction risk. Device protrusion illustrations (bottom) demonstrate the distance the prosthesis projects into the left ventricular cavity (double-sided arrows). The greater the device protrusion, the higher the LVOT obstruction risk."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200027/asset/images/large/rg.2020200027.fig10.jpeg" height="2445" width="2500" aria-labelledby="fig10" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10</span>. Device-specific characteristics affecting neo-LVOT size. Device flaring illustrations (top) show outward angulation (double-sided arrows) of the ventricular side of the prosthesis (green areas). The greater the device flaring, the higher the LVOT obstruction risk. Device protrusion illustrations (bottom) demonstrate the distance the prosthesis projects into the left ventricular cavity (double-sided arrows). The greater the device protrusion, the higher the LVOT obstruction risk.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200027&amp;id=fig10">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11a" class="graphic" aria-label="Factors that increase the risk of neo-LVOT obstruction. (a) Three-chamber long-axis CT image shows the aortomitral angle (AMA) (purple arrows), which is measured between the mitral annulus central axis (red dotted line) and aortic annulus central axis (yellow dotted line). The larger the aortomitral angle, the higher the risk of LVOT obstruction. (b) Three-chamber long-axis CT image obtained at end diastole shows the measurement of the basal interventricular septal thickness (arrows, dotted line). Larger basal septal thickness increases the risk of LVOT obstruction. (c) Three-chamber long-axis CT image shows the AML length as the distance (red solid line) between the tip of the A2 scallop (purple solid circle) and the junction of the hinge point (blue solid circle), or the junction of the leaflet with the posterior aortic annulus. This can be done at both end systole (shown) and end diastole (not shown)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200027/asset/images/large/rg.2020200027.fig11a.jpeg" height="1277" width="1373" aria-labelledby="fig11a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11a</span>. Factors that increase the risk of neo-LVOT obstruction. <b>(a)</b> Three-chamber long-axis CT image shows the aortomitral angle <i>(AMA)</i> (purple arrows), which is measured between the mitral annulus central axis (red dotted line) and aortic annulus central axis (yellow dotted line). The larger the aortomitral angle, the higher the risk of LVOT obstruction. <b>(b)</b> Three-chamber long-axis CT image obtained at end diastole shows the measurement of the basal interventricular septal thickness (arrows, dotted line). Larger basal septal thickness increases the risk of LVOT obstruction. <b>(c)</b> Three-chamber long-axis CT image shows the AML length as the distance (red solid line) between the tip of the A2 scallop (purple solid circle) and the junction of the hinge point (blue solid circle), or the junction of the leaflet with the posterior aortic annulus. This can be done at both end systole (shown) and end diastole (not shown).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200027&amp;id=fig11a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11b" class="graphic" aria-label="Factors that increase the risk of neo-LVOT obstruction. (a) Three-chamber long-axis CT image shows the aortomitral angle (AMA) (purple arrows), which is measured between the mitral annulus central axis (red dotted line) and aortic annulus central axis (yellow dotted line). The larger the aortomitral angle, the higher the risk of LVOT obstruction. (b) Three-chamber long-axis CT image obtained at end diastole shows the measurement of the basal interventricular septal thickness (arrows, dotted line). Larger basal septal thickness increases the risk of LVOT obstruction. (c) Three-chamber long-axis CT image shows the AML length as the distance (red solid line) between the tip of the A2 scallop (purple solid circle) and the junction of the hinge point (blue solid circle), or the junction of the leaflet with the posterior aortic annulus. This can be done at both end systole (shown) and end diastole (not shown)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200027/asset/images/large/rg.2020200027.fig11b.jpeg" height="1277" width="987" aria-labelledby="fig11b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11b</span>. Factors that increase the risk of neo-LVOT obstruction. <b>(a)</b> Three-chamber long-axis CT image shows the aortomitral angle <i>(AMA)</i> (purple arrows), which is measured between the mitral annulus central axis (red dotted line) and aortic annulus central axis (yellow dotted line). The larger the aortomitral angle, the higher the risk of LVOT obstruction. <b>(b)</b> Three-chamber long-axis CT image obtained at end diastole shows the measurement of the basal interventricular septal thickness (arrows, dotted line). Larger basal septal thickness increases the risk of LVOT obstruction. <b>(c)</b> Three-chamber long-axis CT image shows the AML length as the distance (red solid line) between the tip of the A2 scallop (purple solid circle) and the junction of the hinge point (blue solid circle), or the junction of the leaflet with the posterior aortic annulus. This can be done at both end systole (shown) and end diastole (not shown).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200027&amp;id=fig11b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11c" class="graphic" aria-label="Factors that increase the risk of neo-LVOT obstruction. (a) Three-chamber long-axis CT image shows the aortomitral angle (AMA) (purple arrows), which is measured between the mitral annulus central axis (red dotted line) and aortic annulus central axis (yellow dotted line). The larger the aortomitral angle, the higher the risk of LVOT obstruction. (b) Three-chamber long-axis CT image obtained at end diastole shows the measurement of the basal interventricular septal thickness (arrows, dotted line). Larger basal septal thickness increases the risk of LVOT obstruction. (c) Three-chamber long-axis CT image shows the AML length as the distance (red solid line) between the tip of the A2 scallop (purple solid circle) and the junction of the hinge point (blue solid circle), or the junction of the leaflet with the posterior aortic annulus. This can be done at both end systole (shown) and end diastole (not shown)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200027/asset/images/large/rg.2020200027.fig11c.jpeg" height="1277" width="1343" aria-labelledby="fig11c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11c</span>. Factors that increase the risk of neo-LVOT obstruction. <b>(a)</b> Three-chamber long-axis CT image shows the aortomitral angle <i>(AMA)</i> (purple arrows), which is measured between the mitral annulus central axis (red dotted line) and aortic annulus central axis (yellow dotted line). The larger the aortomitral angle, the higher the risk of LVOT obstruction. <b>(b)</b> Three-chamber long-axis CT image obtained at end diastole shows the measurement of the basal interventricular septal thickness (arrows, dotted line). Larger basal septal thickness increases the risk of LVOT obstruction. <b>(c)</b> Three-chamber long-axis CT image shows the AML length as the distance (red solid line) between the tip of the A2 scallop (purple solid circle) and the junction of the hinge point (blue solid circle), or the junction of the leaflet with the posterior aortic annulus. This can be done at both end systole (shown) and end diastole (not shown).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200027&amp;id=fig11c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12a" class="graphic" aria-label="Basal septal thickness and alcohol septal ablation. (a) Illustrations show that the thickness of the septum (horizontal black lines) can be decreased by alcohol septal ablation (left), which is a catheter-directed (black wavy line) delivery of alcohol (*) into a septal perforator branch of the left anterior descending coronary artery. This results in necrosis of a portion of the basal septum and subsequent widening of the LVOT, as depicted on the right illustration. Ao = aorta, LA = left atrium. (b, c) Preprocedure (b) and postprocedure (c) three-chamber long-axis CT images show reduction in basal septal thickness (arrow) and subsequent LVOT widening."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200027/asset/images/large/rg.2020200027.fig12a.jpeg" height="1377" width="2300" aria-labelledby="fig12a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12a</span>. Basal septal thickness and alcohol septal ablation. <b>(a)</b> Illustrations show that the thickness of the septum (horizontal black lines) can be decreased by alcohol septal ablation (left), which is a catheter-directed (black wavy line) delivery of alcohol (*) into a septal perforator branch of the left anterior descending coronary artery. This results in necrosis of a portion of the basal septum and subsequent widening of the LVOT, as depicted on the right illustration. <i>Ao</i> = aorta, <i>LA</i> = left atrium. <b>(b, c)</b> Preprocedure <b>(b)</b> and postprocedure <b>(c)</b> three-chamber long-axis CT images show reduction in basal septal thickness (arrow) and subsequent LVOT widening.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200027&amp;id=fig12a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12b" class="graphic" aria-label="Basal septal thickness and alcohol septal ablation. (a) Illustrations show that the thickness of the septum (horizontal black lines) can be decreased by alcohol septal ablation (left), which is a catheter-directed (black wavy line) delivery of alcohol (*) into a septal perforator branch of the left anterior descending coronary artery. This results in necrosis of a portion of the basal septum and subsequent widening of the LVOT, as depicted on the right illustration. Ao = aorta, LA = left atrium. (b, c) Preprocedure (b) and postprocedure (c) three-chamber long-axis CT images show reduction in basal septal thickness (arrow) and subsequent LVOT widening."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200027/asset/images/large/rg.2020200027.fig12b.jpeg" height="1302" width="1078" aria-labelledby="fig12b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12b</span>. Basal septal thickness and alcohol septal ablation. <b>(a)</b> Illustrations show that the thickness of the septum (horizontal black lines) can be decreased by alcohol septal ablation (left), which is a catheter-directed (black wavy line) delivery of alcohol (*) into a septal perforator branch of the left anterior descending coronary artery. This results in necrosis of a portion of the basal septum and subsequent widening of the LVOT, as depicted on the right illustration. <i>Ao</i> = aorta, <i>LA</i> = left atrium. <b>(b, c)</b> Preprocedure <b>(b)</b> and postprocedure <b>(c)</b> three-chamber long-axis CT images show reduction in basal septal thickness (arrow) and subsequent LVOT widening.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200027&amp;id=fig12b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12c" class="graphic" aria-label="Basal septal thickness and alcohol septal ablation. (a) Illustrations show that the thickness of the septum (horizontal black lines) can be decreased by alcohol septal ablation (left), which is a catheter-directed (black wavy line) delivery of alcohol (*) into a septal perforator branch of the left anterior descending coronary artery. This results in necrosis of a portion of the basal septum and subsequent widening of the LVOT, as depicted on the right illustration. Ao = aorta, LA = left atrium. (b, c) Preprocedure (b) and postprocedure (c) three-chamber long-axis CT images show reduction in basal septal thickness (arrow) and subsequent LVOT widening."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200027/asset/images/large/rg.2020200027.fig12c.jpeg" height="1302" width="1173" aria-labelledby="fig12c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12c</span>. Basal septal thickness and alcohol septal ablation. <b>(a)</b> Illustrations show that the thickness of the septum (horizontal black lines) can be decreased by alcohol septal ablation (left), which is a catheter-directed (black wavy line) delivery of alcohol (*) into a septal perforator branch of the left anterior descending coronary artery. This results in necrosis of a portion of the basal septum and subsequent widening of the LVOT, as depicted on the right illustration. <i>Ao</i> = aorta, <i>LA</i> = left atrium. <b>(b, c)</b> Preprocedure <b>(b)</b> and postprocedure <b>(c)</b> three-chamber long-axis CT images show reduction in basal septal thickness (arrow) and subsequent LVOT widening.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200027&amp;id=fig12c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13" class="graphic" aria-label="LAMPOON procedure. Schematic drawings of views down the LVOT from the LV demonstrate how the LAMPOON procedure widens the LVOT. The LVOT is narrowed by the AML (blue area) (top). A longer AML length causes a narrower LVOT area. The LAMPOON procedure is performed by radially lacerating the AML, typically through the A2 scallop (dotted arrow). Following the LAMPOON procedure (bottom), the lacerated AML creates a wider LVOT area."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200027/asset/images/large/rg.2020200027.fig13.jpeg" height="2085" width="1500" aria-labelledby="fig13" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13</span>. LAMPOON procedure. Schematic drawings of views down the LVOT from the LV demonstrate how the LAMPOON procedure widens the LVOT. The LVOT is narrowed by the AML (blue area) (top). A longer AML length causes a narrower LVOT area. The LAMPOON procedure is performed by radially lacerating the AML, typically through the A2 scallop (dotted arrow). Following the LAMPOON procedure (bottom), the lacerated AML creates a wider LVOT area.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200027&amp;id=fig13">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14a" class="graphic" aria-label="Simulating procedural fluoroscopic angles. (a) Mitral annular short-axis CT image shows that the SL and trigone-trigone (TT) fluoroscopic views have a line of sight parallel to the SL (red dashed line) and trigone-trigone (purple dashed line) distance lines, respectively. The compromise view is depicted along a virtual line (green dashed line), approximately midway between the SL and trigone-trigone distance lines. (b, c) Simulated 3D-rendered CT image in the compromise view (b) best shows potential LVOT narrowing (yellow arrows), while the simulated 3D-rendered CT image in the SL view (c) is best for aligning the prosthesis along the mitral annulus central axis (dotted arrow). Images were obtained by using Intuition (version 4.4.13; Terarecon, Durham, N.C.). CAU = caudal, CRA = cranial, RAO = right anterior oblique. (d, e) Simulated fluoroscopic coplanar views generated from CT data obtained with 3mensio Structural Heart Mitral workflow (version 10.1, Pie Medical Imaging, Maastricht, the Netherlands) show the mitral annulus (arrow in d) and virtual valve placement (arrow in e) in a valve deployment angle as part of procedural planning. The coplanar angle is usually RAO or RAO caudal. (f) Screen shot shows a four-chamber long-axis CT image obtained perpendicular to the annulus plane (top left), short-axis CT image of the annulus plane (top right), and corresponding simulated fluoroscopic view for the top left CT image (bottom left). Graph (bottom right) created by using cvi42 (version 5.11; Circle Cardiovascular Imaging, Calgary, Alberta, Canada) shows a coplanar curve that shows the sinusoidal path the C-arm will follow as it rotates around the patient and provides a tangential view of the valve."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200027/asset/images/large/rg.2020200027.fig14a.jpeg" height="1134" width="896" aria-labelledby="fig14a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14a</span>. Simulating procedural fluoroscopic angles. <b>(a)</b> Mitral annular short-axis CT image shows that the SL and trigone-trigone <i>(TT)</i> fluoroscopic views have a line of sight parallel to the SL (red dashed line) and trigone-trigone (purple dashed line) distance lines, respectively. The compromise view is depicted along a virtual line (green dashed line), approximately midway between the SL and trigone-trigone distance lines. <b>(b, c)</b> Simulated 3D-rendered CT image in the compromise view <b>(b)</b> best shows potential LVOT narrowing (yellow arrows), while the simulated 3D-rendered CT image in the SL view <b>(c)</b> is best for aligning the prosthesis along the mitral annulus central axis (dotted arrow). Images were obtained by using Intuition (version 4.4.13; Terarecon, Durham, N.C.). <i>CAU</i> = caudal, <i>CRA</i> = cranial, <i>RAO</i> = right anterior oblique. <b>(d, e)</b> Simulated fluoroscopic coplanar views generated from CT data obtained with 3mensio Structural Heart Mitral workflow (version 10.1, Pie Medical Imaging, Maastricht, the Netherlands) show the mitral annulus (arrow in <b>d</b>) and virtual valve placement (arrow in <b>e</b>) in a valve deployment angle as part of procedural planning. The coplanar angle is usually RAO or RAO caudal. <b>(f)</b> Screen shot shows a four-chamber long-axis CT image obtained perpendicular to the annulus plane (top left), short-axis CT image of the annulus plane (top right), and corresponding simulated fluoroscopic view for the top left CT image (bottom left). Graph (bottom right) created by using cvi42 (version 5.11; Circle Cardiovascular Imaging, Calgary, Alberta, Canada) shows a coplanar curve that shows the sinusoidal path the C-arm will follow as it rotates around the patient and provides a tangential view of the valve.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200027&amp;id=fig14a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14b" class="graphic" aria-label="Simulating procedural fluoroscopic angles. (a) Mitral annular short-axis CT image shows that the SL and trigone-trigone (TT) fluoroscopic views have a line of sight parallel to the SL (red dashed line) and trigone-trigone (purple dashed line) distance lines, respectively. The compromise view is depicted along a virtual line (green dashed line), approximately midway between the SL and trigone-trigone distance lines. (b, c) Simulated 3D-rendered CT image in the compromise view (b) best shows potential LVOT narrowing (yellow arrows), while the simulated 3D-rendered CT image in the SL view (c) is best for aligning the prosthesis along the mitral annulus central axis (dotted arrow). Images were obtained by using Intuition (version 4.4.13; Terarecon, Durham, N.C.). CAU = caudal, CRA = cranial, RAO = right anterior oblique. (d, e) Simulated fluoroscopic coplanar views generated from CT data obtained with 3mensio Structural Heart Mitral workflow (version 10.1, Pie Medical Imaging, Maastricht, the Netherlands) show the mitral annulus (arrow in d) and virtual valve placement (arrow in e) in a valve deployment angle as part of procedural planning. The coplanar angle is usually RAO o