ning. The coplanar angle is usually RAO or RAO caudal. (f) Screen shot shows a four-chamber long-axis CT image obtained perpendicular to the annulus plane (top left), short-axis CT image of the annulus plane (top right), and corresponding simulated fluoroscopic view for the top left CT image (bottom left). Graph (bottom right) created by using cvi42 (version 5.11; Circle Cardiovascular Imaging, Calgary, Alberta, Canada) shows a coplanar curve that shows the sinusoidal path the C-arm will follow as it rotates around the patient and provides a tangential view of the valve."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200027/asset/images/large/rg.2020200027.fig14c.jpeg" height="1134" width="1492" aria-labelledby="fig14c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14c</span>. Simulating procedural fluoroscopic angles. <b>(a)</b> Mitral annular short-axis CT image shows that the SL and trigone-trigone <i>(TT)</i> fluoroscopic views have a line of sight parallel to the SL (red dashed line) and trigone-trigone (purple dashed line) distance lines, respectively. The compromise view is depicted along a virtual line (green dashed line), approximately midway between the SL and trigone-trigone distance lines. <b>(b, c)</b> Simulated 3D-rendered CT image in the compromise view <b>(b)</b> best shows potential LVOT narrowing (yellow arrows), while the simulated 3D-rendered CT image in the SL view <b>(c)</b> is best for aligning the prosthesis along the mitral annulus central axis (dotted arrow). Images were obtained by using Intuition (version 4.4.13; Terarecon, Durham, N.C.). <i>CAU</i> = caudal, <i>CRA</i> = cranial, <i>RAO</i> = right anterior oblique. <b>(d, e)</b> Simulated fluoroscopic coplanar views generated from CT data obtained with 3mensio Structural Heart Mitral workflow (version 10.1, Pie Medical Imaging, Maastricht, the Netherlands) show the mitral annulus (arrow in <b>d</b>) and virtual valve placement (arrow in <b>e</b>) in a valve deployment angle as part of proce