tral annulus (arrow in d) and virtual valve placement (arrow in e) in a valve deployment angle as part of procedural planning. The coplanar angle is usually RAO or RAO caudal. (f) Screen shot shows a four-chamber long-axis CT image obtained perpendicular to the annulus plane (top left), short-axis CT image of the annulus plane (top right), and corresponding simulated fluoroscopic view for the top left CT image (bottom left). Graph (bottom right) created by using cvi42 (version 5.11; Circle Cardiovascular Imaging, Calgary, Alberta, Canada) shows a coplanar curve that shows the sinusoidal path the C-arm will follow as it rotates around the patient and provides a tangential view of the valve."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200027/asset/images/large/rg.2020200027.fig14f.jpeg" height="2836" width="3799" aria-labelledby="fig14f" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14f</span>. Simulating procedural fluoroscopic angles. <b>(a)</b> Mitral annular short-axis CT image shows that the SL and trigone-trigone <i>(TT)</i> fluoroscopic views have a line of sight parallel to the SL (red dashed line) and trigone-trigone (purple dashed line) distance lines, respectively. The compromise view is depicted along a virtual line (green dashed line), approximately midway between the SL and trigone-trigone distance lines. <b>(b, c)</b> Simulated 3D-rendered CT image in the compromise view <b>(b)</b> best shows potential LVOT narrowing (yellow arrows), while the simulated 3D-rendered CT image in the SL view <b>(c)</b> is best for aligning the prosthesis along the mitral annulus central axis (dotted arrow). Images were obtained by using Intuition (version 4.4.13; Terarecon, Durham, N.C.). <i>CAU</i> = caudal, <i>CRA</i> = cranial, <i>RAO</i> = right anterior oblique. <b>(d, e)</b> Simulated fluoroscopic coplanar views generated from CT data obtained with 3mensio Structural Heart Mitral workflow (version 10.1, Pie Medical Imaging, Maastricht, the Netherlands) show the mitral annulus (arrow in <b>d</b>) and virtual valve placement (arrow in <b>e</b>) in a valve deployment angle as part of procedural planning. The coplanar angle is usually RAO or RAO caudal. <b>(f)</b> Screen shot shows a four-chamber long-axis CT image obtained perpendicular to the annulus plane (top left), short-axis CT image of the annulus plane (top right), and corresponding simulated fluoroscopic view for the top left CT image (bottom left). Graph (bottom right) created by using cvi42 (version 5.11; Circle Cardiovascular Imaging, Calgary, Alberta, Canada) shows a coplanar curve that shows the sinusoidal path the C-arm will follow as it rotates around the patient and provides a tangential view of the valve.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200027&amp;id=fig14f">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig15a" class="graphic" aria-label="MAC. (a) Short-axis maximum intensity projection reconstructed CT image of the mitral annulus plane shows exuberant MAC, predominantly involving the posterior annulus (arrows). (b) Short-axis multiplanar reformatted CT image shows a solid and nodular MAC (arrows). (c) Short-axis multiplanar reformatted CT image in another patient shows caseous MAC (arrows), with liquefactive calcium in the center (*). The presence of solid MAC has a greater impact on device anchoring than does caseous MAC."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200027/asset/images/large/rg.2020200027.fig15a.jpeg" height="1327" width="1194" aria-labelledby="fig15a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 15a</span>. MAC. <b>(a)</b> Short-axis maximum intensity projection reconstructed CT image of the mitral annulus plane shows exuberant MAC, predominantly involving the posterior annulus (arrows). <b>(b)</b> Short-axis multiplanar reformatted CT image shows a solid and nodular MAC (arrows). <b>(c)</b> Short-axis multiplanar reformatted CT image in another patient shows caseous MAC (arrows), with liquefactive calcium in the center (*). The presence of solid MAC has a greater impact on device anchoring than does caseous MAC.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200027&amp;id=fig15a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig15b" class="graphic" aria-label="MAC. (a) Short-axis maximum intensity projection reconstructed CT image of the mitral annulus plane shows exuberant MAC, predominantly involving the posterior annulus (arrows). (b) Short-axis multiplanar reformatted CT image shows a solid and nodular MAC (arrows). (c) Short-axis multiplanar reformatted CT image in another patient shows caseous MAC (arrows), with liquefactive calcium in the center (*). The presence of solid MAC has a greater impact on device anchoring than does caseous MAC."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200027/asset/images/large/rg.2020200027.fig15b.jpeg" height="1327" width="1329" aria-labelledby="fig15b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 15b</span>. MAC. <b>(a)</b> Short-axis maximum intensity projection reconstructed CT image of the mitral annulus plane shows exuberant MAC, predominantly involving the posterior annulus (arrows). <b>(b)</b> Short-axis multiplanar reformatted CT image shows a solid and nodular MAC (arrows). <b>(c)</b> Short-axis multiplanar reformatted CT image in another patient shows caseous MAC (arrows), with liquefactive calcium in the center (*). The presence of solid MAC has a greater impact on device anchoring than does caseous MAC.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200027&amp;id=fig15b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig15c" class="graphic" aria-label="MAC. (a) Short-axis maximum intensity projection reconstructed CT image of the mitral annulus plane shows exuberant MAC, predominantly involving the posterior annulus (arrows). (b) Short-axis multiplanar reformatted CT image shows a solid and nodular MAC (arrows). (c) Short-axis multiplanar reformatted CT image in another patient shows caseous MAC (arrows), with liquefactive calcium in the center (*). The presence of solid MAC has a greater impact on device anchoring than does caseous MAC."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200027/asset/images/large/rg.2020200027.fig15c.jpeg" height="1327" width="1177" aria-labelledby="fig15c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 15c</span>. MAC. <b>(a)</b> Short-axis maximum intensity projection reconstructed CT image of the mitral annulus plane shows exuberant MAC, predominantly involving the posterior annulus (arrows). <b>(b)</b> Short-axis multiplanar reformatted CT image shows a solid and nodular MAC (arrows). <b>(c)</b> Short-axis multiplanar reformatted CT image in another patient shows caseous MAC (arrows), with liquefactive calcium in the center (*). The presence of solid MAC has a greater impact on device anchoring than does caseous MAC.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200027&amp;id=fig15c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig16a" class="graphic" aria-label="Landing zone characteristics. (a) Three-chamber long-axis reconstructed CT image at end diastole in a patient with functional mitral regurgitation shows a myocardial shelf (arrow), often seen at the posterior mitral leaflet insertion point at end diastole. Double-headed arrow = extent of the myocardial shelf. (b) Three-chamber long-axis CT image in the same patient at end systole shows that the shelf (arrow) is less apparent or even absent. The myocardial shelf has anchoring relevance for devices like Tiara. The depth from the posterior leaflet insertion point to the bottom of the shelf should be measured on three-chamber views at end systole and end diastole. Double-headed arrow = extent of the myocardial shelf. (c) Three-chamber long-axis CT image shows disjunction of the posterior mitral leaflet from its insertion site (blue arrow). The double-headed red arrow represents the 12-mm disjunction between the mitral leaflet and LV myocardium."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200027/asset/images/large/rg.2020200027.fig16a.jpeg" height="1185" width="1500" aria-labelledby="fig16a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 16a</span>. Landing zone characteristics. <b>(a)</b> Three-chamber long-axis reconstructed CT image at end diastole in a patient with functional mitral regurgitation shows a myocardial shelf (arrow), often seen at the posterior mitral leaflet insertion point at end diastole. Double-headed arrow = extent of the myocardial shelf. <b>(b)</b> Three-chamber long-axis CT image in the same patient at end systole shows that the shelf (arrow) is less apparent or even absent. The myocardial shelf has anchoring relevance for devices like Tiara. The depth from the posterior leaflet insertion point to the bottom of the shelf should be measured on three-chamber views at end systole and end diastole. Double-headed arrow = extent of the myocardial shelf. <b>(c)</b> Three-chamber long-axis CT image shows disjunction of the posterior mitral leaflet from its insertion site (blue arrow). The double-headed red arrow represents the 12-mm disjunction between the mitral leaflet and LV myocardium.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200027&amp;id=fig16a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig16b" class="graphic" aria-label="Landing zone characteristics. (a) Three-chamber long-axis reconstructed CT image at end diastole in a patient with functional mitral regurgitation shows a myocardial shelf (arrow), often seen at the posterior mitral leaflet insertion point at end diastole. Double-headed arrow = extent of the myocardial shelf. (b) Three-chamber long-axis CT image in the same patient at end systole shows that the shelf (arrow) is less apparent or even absent. The myocardial shelf has anchoring relevance for devices like Tiara. The depth from the posterior leaflet insertion point to the bottom of the shelf should be measured on three-chamber views at end systole and end diastole. Double-headed arrow = extent of the myocardial shelf. (c) Three-chamber long-axis CT image shows disjunction of the posterior mitral leaflet from its insertion site (blue arrow). The double-headed red arrow represents the 12-mm disjunction between the mitral leaflet and LV myocardium."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200027/asset/images/large/rg.2020200027.fig16b.jpeg" height="1073" width="1496" aria-labelledby="fig16b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 16b</span>. Landing zone characteristics. <b>(a)</b> Three-chamber long-axis reconstructed CT image at end diastole in a patient with functional mitral regurgitation shows a myocardial shelf (arrow), often seen at the posterior mitral leaflet insertion point at end diastole. Double-headed arrow = extent of the myocardial shelf. <b>(b)</b> Three-chamber long-axis CT image in the same patient at end systole shows that the shelf (arrow) is less apparent or even absent. The myocardial shelf has anchoring relevance for devices like Tiara. The depth from the posterior leaflet insertion point to the bottom of the shelf should be measured on three-chamber views at end systole and end diastole. Double-headed arrow = extent of the myocardial shelf. <b>(c)</b> Three-chamber long-axis CT image shows disjunction of the posterior mitral leaflet from its insertion site (blue arrow). The double-headed red arrow represents the 12-mm disjunction between the mitral leaflet and LV myocardium.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200027&amp;id=fig16b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig16c" class="graphic" aria-label="Landing zone characteristics. (a) Three-chamber long-axis reconstructed CT image at end diastole in a patient with functional mitral regurgitation shows a myocardial shelf (arrow), often seen at the posterior mitral leaflet insertion point at end diastole. Double-headed arrow = extent of the myocardial shelf. (b) Three-chamber long-axis CT image in the same patient at end systole shows that the shelf (arrow) is less apparent or even absent. The myocardial shelf has anchoring relevance for devices like Tiara. The depth from the posterior leaflet insertion point to the bottom of the shelf should be measured on three-chamber views at end systole and end diastole. Double-headed arrow = extent of the myocardial shelf. (c) Three-chamber long-axis CT image shows disjunction of the posterior mitral leaflet from its insertion site (blue arrow). The double-headed red arrow represents the 12-mm disjunction between the mitral leaflet and LV myocardium."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200027/asset/images/large/rg.2020200027.fig16c.jpeg" height="1073" width="1453" aria-labelledby="fig16c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 16c</span>. Landing zone characteristics. <b>(a)</b> Three-chamber long-axis reconstructed CT image at end diastole in a patient with functional mitral regurgitation shows a myocardial shelf (arrow), often seen at the posterior mitral leaflet insertion point at end diastole. Double-headed arrow = extent of the myocardial shelf. <b>(b)</b> Three-chamber long-axis CT image in the same patient at end systole shows that the shelf (arrow) is less apparent or even absent. The myocardial shelf has anchoring relevance for devices like Tiara. The depth from the posterior leaflet insertion point to the bottom of the shelf should be measured on three-chamber views at end systole and end diastole. Double-headed arrow = extent of the myocardial shelf. <b>(c)</b> Three-chamber long-axis CT image shows disjunction of the posterior mitral leaflet from its insertion site (blue arrow). The double-headed red arrow represents the 12-mm disjunction between the mitral leaflet and LV myocardium.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200027&amp;id=fig16c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig17a" class="graphic" aria-label="Vascular structures adjacent the mitral annulus. Virtual fluoroscopic images (a, b) show CT postprocessing software simulating a guidewire in the coronary sinus (green lines in a–c) to use as a fluoroscopic marker during valve deployment. Similarly, the course of the LCX (arrows in d) adjacent to the mitral annulus can be simulated on virtual fluoroscopic (c) and maximum-intensity projection (d) images (arrows in d)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200027/asset/images/large/rg.2020200027.fig17a.jpeg" height="1232" width="1475" aria-labelledby="fig17a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 17a</span>. Vascular structures adjacent the mitral annulus. Virtual fluoroscopic images <b>(a, b)</b> show CT postprocessing software simulating a guidewire in the coronary sinus (green lines in <b>a–c</b>) to use as a fluoroscopic marker during valve deployment. Similarly, the course of the LCX (arrows in <b>d</b>) adjacent to the mitral annulus can be simulated on virtual fluoroscopic <b>(c)</b> and maximum-intensity projection <b>(d)</b> images (arrows in <b>d</b>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200027&amp;id=fig17a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig17b" class="graphic" aria-label="Vascular structures adjacent the mitral annulus. Virtual fluoroscopic images (a, b) show CT postprocessing software simulating a guidewire in the coronary sinus (green lines in a–c) to use as a fluoroscopic marker during valve deployment. Similarly, the course of the LCX (arrows in d) adjacent to the mitral annulus can be simulated on virtual fluoroscopic (c) and maximum-intensity projection (d) images (arrows in d)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200027/asset/images/large/rg.2020200027.fig17b.jpeg" height="1232" width="1475" aria-labelledby="fig17b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 17b</span>. Vascular structures adjacent the mitral annulus. Virtual fluoroscopic images <b>(a, b)</b> show CT postprocessing software simulating a guidewire in the coronary sinus (green lines in <b>a–c</b>) to use as a fluoroscopic marker during valve deployment. Similarly, the course of the LCX (arrows in <b>d</b>) adjacent to the mitral annulus can be simulated on virtual fluoroscopic <b>(c)</b> and maximum-intensity projection <b>(d)</b> images (arrows in <b>d</b>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200027&amp;id=fig17b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig17c" class="graphic" aria-label="Vascular structures adjacent the mitral annulus. Virtual fluoroscopic images (a, b) show CT postprocessing software simulating a guidewire in the coronary sinus (green lines in a–c) to use as a fluoroscopic marker during valve deployment. Similarly, the course of the LCX (arrows in d) adjacent to the mitral annulus can be simulated on virtual fluoroscopic (c) and maximum-intensity projection (d) images (arrows in d)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200027/asset/images/large/rg.2020200027.fig17c.jpeg" height="1292" width="1572" aria-labelledby="fig17c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 17c</span>. Vascular structures adjacent the mitral annulus. Virtual fluoroscopic images <b>(a, b)</b> show CT postprocessing software simulating a guidewire in the coronary sinus (green lines in <b>a–c</b>) to use as a fluoroscopic marker during valve deployment. Similarly, the course of the LCX (arrows in <b>d</b>) adjacent to the mitral annulus can be simulated on virtual fluoroscopic <b>(c)</b> and maximum-intensity projection <b>(d)</b> images (arrows in <b>d</b>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200027&amp;id=fig17c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig17d" class="graphic" aria-label="Vascular structures adjacent the mitral annulus. Virtual fluoroscopic images (a, b) show CT postprocessing software simulating a guidewire in the coronary sinus (green lines in a–c) to use as a fluoroscopic marker during valve deployment. Similarly, the course of the LCX (arrows in d) adjacent to the mitral annulus can be simulated on virtual fluoroscopic (c) and maximum-intensity projection (d) images (arrows in d)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200027/asset/images/large/rg.2020200027.fig17d.jpeg" height="1287" width="1371" aria-labelledby="fig17d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 17d</span>. Vascular structures adjacent the mitral annulus. Virtual fluoroscopic images <b>(a, b)</b> show CT postprocessing software simulating a guidewire in the coronary sinus (green lines in <b>a–c</b>) to use as a fluoroscopic marker during valve deployment. Similarly, the course of the LCX (arrows in <b>d</b>) adjacent to the mitral annulus can be simulated on virtual fluoroscopic <b>(c)</b> and maximum-intensity projection <b>(d)</b> images (arrows in <b>d</b>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200027&amp;id=fig17d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig18a" class="graphic" aria-label="Subvalvular apparatus measurements. (a) Three-chamber long-axis volumetric CT image shows the distance (double-headed arrow) between the left atrial appendage ostium and mitral annulus plane (dashed line). (b) Two-chamber long-axis CT image shows the distances (double-headed arrows) between the papillary muscle heads and mitral annulus plane (dashed line). (c) Short-axis CT image shows the distance between the papillary muscle bellies (yellow double-headed arrow) and separation between the muscle bellies and LV wall (red double-headed arrows)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200027/asset/images/large/rg.2020200027.fig18a.jpeg" height="1425" width="1215" aria-labelledby="fig18a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 18a</span>. Subvalvular apparatus measurements. <b>(a)</b> Three-chamber long-axis volumetric CT image shows the distance (double-headed arrow) between the left atrial appendage ostium and mitral annulus plane (dashed line). <b>(b)</b> Two-chamber long-axis CT image shows the distances (double-headed arrows) between the papillary muscle heads and mitral annulus plane (dashed line). <b>(c)</b> Short-axis CT image shows the distance between the papillary muscle bellies (yellow double-headed arrow) and separation between the muscle bellies and LV wall (red double-headed arrows).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200027&amp;id=fig18a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig18b" class="graphic" aria-label="Subvalvular apparatus measurements. (a) Three-chamber long-axis volumetric CT image shows the distance (double-headed arrow) between the left atrial appendage ostium and mitral annulus plane (dashed line). (b) Two-chamber long-axis CT image shows the distances (double-headed arrows) between the papillary muscle heads and mitral annulus plane (dashed line). (c) Short-axis CT image shows the distance between the papillary muscle bellies (yellow double-headed arrow) and separation between the muscle bellies and LV wall (red double-headed arrows)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200027/asset/images/large/rg.2020200027.fig18b.jpeg" height="1425" width="1410" aria-labelledby="fig18b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 18b</span>. Subvalvular apparatus measurements. <b>(a)</b> Three-chamber long-axis volumetric CT image shows the distance (double-headed arrow) between the left atrial appendage ostium and mitral annulus plane (dashed line). <b>(b)</b> Two-chamber long-axis CT image shows the distances (double-headed arrows) between the papillary muscle heads and mitral annulus plane (dashed line). <b>(c)</b> Short-axis CT image shows the distance between the papillary muscle bellies (yellow double-headed arrow) and separation between the muscle bellies and LV wall (red double-headed arrows).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200027&amp;id=fig18b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig18c" class="graphic" aria-label="Subvalvular apparatus measurements. (a) Three-chamber long-axis volumetric CT image shows the distance (double-headed arrow) between the left atrial appendage ostium and mitral annulus plane (dashed line). (b) Two-chamber long-axis CT image shows the distances (double-headed arrows) between the papillary muscle heads and mitral annulus plane (dashed line). (c) Short-axis CT image shows the distance between the papillary muscle bellies (yellow double-headed arrow) and separation between the muscle bellies and LV wall (red double-headed arrows)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200027/asset/images/large/rg.2020200027.fig18c.jpeg" height="1425" width="1074" aria-labelledby="fig18c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 18c</span>. Subvalvular apparatus measurements. <b>(a)</b> Three-chamber long-axis volumetric CT image shows the distance (double-headed arrow) between the left atrial appendage ostium and mitral annulus plane (dashed line). <b>(b)</b> Two-chamber long-axis CT image shows the distances (double-headed arrows) between the papillary muscle heads and mitral annulus plane (dashed line). <b>(c)</b> Short-axis CT image shows the distance between the papillary muscle bellies (yellow double-headed arrow) and separation between the muscle bellies and LV wall (red double-headed arrows).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200027&amp;id=fig18c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig19a" class="graphic" aria-label="Planning for transapical access and closure. Volumetric CT images can help determine the intercostal space closest to the LV apex best for transapical approach (yellow arrow), as depicted on the sagittal image (a). The best fluoroscopic angle for transapical coaxial approach relative to the mitral annulus plane (white line in b) can be simulated, as depicted on the coronal oblique image (b). Note the slight offset between the coaxial approach, LV central axis (dotted green line in b), and mitral annulus central axis (dotted blue line in b)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200027/asset/images/large/rg.2020200027.fig19a.jpeg" height="1487" width="1302" aria-labelledby="fig19a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 19a</span>. Planning for transapical access and closure. Volumetric CT images can help determine the intercostal space closest to the LV apex best for transapical approach (yellow arrow), as depicted on the sagittal image <b>(a)</b>. The best fluoroscopic angle for transapical coaxial approach relative to the mitral annulus plane (white line in <b>b</b>) can be simulated, as depicted on the coronal oblique image <b>(b)</b>. Note the slight offset between the coaxial approach, LV central axis (dotted green line in <b>b</b>), and mitral annulus central axis (dotted blue line in <b>b</b>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200027&amp;id=fig19a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig19b" class="graphic" aria-label="Planning for transapical access and closure. Volumetric CT images can help determine the intercostal space closest to the LV apex best for transapical approach (yellow arrow), as depicted on the sagittal image (a). The best fluoroscopic angle for transapical coaxial approach relative to the mitral annulus plane (white line in b) can be simulated, as depicted on the coronal oblique image (b). Note the slight offset between the coaxial approach, LV central axis (dotted green line in b), and mitral annulus central axis (dotted blue line in b)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200027/asset/images/large/rg.2020200027.fig19b.jpeg" height="1487" width="1348" aria-labelledby="fig19b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 19b</span>. Planning for transapical access and closure. Volumetric CT images can help determine the intercostal space closest to the LV apex best for transapical approach (yellow arrow), as depicted on the sagittal image <b>(a)</b>. The best fluoroscopic angle for transapical coaxial approach relative to the mitral annulus plane (white line in <b>b</b>) can be simulated, as depicted on the coronal oblique image <b>(b)</b>. Note the slight offset between the coaxial approach, LV central axis (dotted green line in <b>b</b>), and mitral annulus central axis (dotted blue line in <b>b</b>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200027&amp;id=fig19b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig20a" class="graphic" aria-label="Cardiac CT-based analysis for transseptal puncture planning using 3mensio Structural Heart Mitral workflow, version 10.1. (a) Simulated anteroposterior fluoroscopic image generated from cardiac CT data shows the fossa ovalis (arrow). (b) Simulated fluoroscopic image generated from cardiac CT data in the valve deployment angle shows the distance between the transseptal puncture (straight arrow) and mitral annulus (curved arrow), measured for procedural planning."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200027/asset/images/large/rg.2020200027.fig20a.jpeg" height="1155" width="1684" aria-labelledby="fig20a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 20a</span>. Cardiac CT-based analysis for transseptal puncture planning using 3mensio Structural Heart Mitral workflow, version 10.1. <b>(a)</b> Simulated anteroposterior fluoroscopic image generated from cardiac CT data shows the fossa ovalis (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Simulated fluoroscopic image generated from cardiac CT data in the valve deployment angle shows the distance between the transseptal puncture (straight arrow) and mitral annulus (curved arrow), measured for procedural planning.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200027&amp;id=fig20a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig20b" class="graphic" aria-label="Cardiac CT-based analysis for transseptal puncture planning using 3mensio Structural Heart Mitral workflow, version 10.1. (a) Simulated anteroposterior fluoroscopic image generated from cardiac CT data shows the fossa ovalis (arrow). (b) Simulated fluoroscopic image generated from cardiac CT data in the valve deployment angle shows the distance between the transseptal puncture (straight arrow) and mitral annulus (curved arrow), measured for procedural planning."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200027/asset/images/large/rg.2020200027.fig20b.jpeg" height="1155" width="1665" aria-labelledby="fig20b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 20b</span>. Cardiac CT-based analysis for transseptal puncture planning using 3mensio Structural Heart Mitral workflow, version 10.1. <b>(a)</b> Simulated anteroposterior fluoroscopic image generated from cardiac CT data shows the fossa ovalis (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Simulated fluoroscopic image generated from cardiac CT data in the valve deployment angle shows the distance between the transseptal puncture (straight arrow) and mitral annulus (curved arrow), measured for procedural planning.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200027&amp;id=fig20b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig21a" class="graphic" aria-label="CT analysis for mitral valve-in-valve procedure. Short-axis CT images show the bioprosthetic valve with thickening of the leaflets (a) and the measurement of the mitral annulus (b)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200027/asset/images/large/rg.2020200027.fig21a.jpeg" height="1460" width="1639" aria-labelledby="fig21a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 21a</span>. CT analysis for mitral valve-in-valve procedure. Short-axis CT images show the bioprosthetic valve with thickening of the leaflets <b>(a)</b> and the measurement of the mitral annulus <b>(b)</b>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200027&amp;id=fig21a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig21b" class="graphic" aria-label="CT analysis for mitral valve-in-valve procedure. Short-axis CT images show the bioprosthetic valve with thickening of the leaflets (a) and the measurement of the mitral annulus (b)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200027/asset/images/large/rg.2020200027.fig21b.jpeg" height="1460" width="1011" aria-labelledby="fig21b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 21b</span>. CT analysis for mitral valve-in-valve procedure. Short-axis CT images show the bioprosthetic valve with thickening of the leaflets <b>(a)</b> and the measurement of the mitral annulus <b>(b)</b>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200027&amp;id=fig21b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig22" class="graphic" aria-label="Valve-in-MAC procedure. Short-axis reconstructed CT image shows the measurement of the mitral annulus (red outline) in a patient with extensive MAC. Note that the inner border of the MAC is traced smoothly, disregarding the finer contour irregularities, assuming that the annulus is a harmonious smoothly marginated entity. Yellow dots = trigones."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200027/asset/images/large/rg.2020200027.fig22.jpeg" height="1747" width="1800" aria-labelledby="fig22" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 22</span>. Valve-in-MAC procedure. Short-axis reconstructed CT image shows the measurement of the mitral annulus (red outline) in a patient with extensive MAC. Note that the inner border of the MAC is traced smoothly, disregarding the finer contour irregularities, assuming that the annulus is a harmonious smoothly marginated entity. Yellow dots = trigones.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200027&amp;id=fig22">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig23a" class="graphic" aria-label="3D printing for TMVR. (a) 3D digital model of the mitral annulus with a digital valve in situ (curved arrow) shows narrowing of LVOT (straight arrow). (b) Photograph shows a 3D printed model, which can be used for device sizing and simulating the procedure."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200027/asset/images/large/rg.2020200027.fig23a.jpeg" height="1161" width="1653" aria-labelledby="fig23a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 23a</span>. 3D printing for TMVR. <b>(a)</b> 3D digital model of the mitral annulus with a digital valve in situ (curved arrow) shows narrowing of LVOT (straight arrow). <b>(b)</b> Photograph shows a 3D printed model, which can be used for device sizing and simulating the procedure.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200027&amp;id=fig23a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig23b" class="graphic" aria-label="3D printing for TMVR. (a) 3D digital model of the mitral annulus with a digital valve in situ (curved arrow) shows narrowing of LVOT (straight arrow). (b) Photograph shows a 3D printed model, which can be used for device sizing and simulating the procedure."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200027/asset/images/large/rg.2020200027.fig23b.jpeg" height="1161" width="1296" aria-labelledby="fig23b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 23b</span>. 3D printing for TMVR. <b>(a)</b> 3D digital model of the mitral annulus with a digital valve in situ (curved arrow) shows narrowing of LVOT (straight arrow). <b>(b)</b> Photograph shows a 3D printed model, which can be used for device sizing and simulating the procedure.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200027&amp;id=fig23b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig24a" class="graphic" aria-label="Normal appearances of TMVR devices following implantation. (a) Two-chamber long-axis CT reconstruction shows the normal appearance of a Sapien 3 device in the mitral position (arrow). (b) Two-chamber long-axis CT reconstruction shows the normal appearance of a Tendyne TMVR device (arrow)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200027/asset/images/large/rg.2020200027.fig24a.jpeg" height="1418" width="1485" aria-labelledby="fig24a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 24a</span>. Normal appearances of TMVR devices following implantation. <b>(a)</b> Two-chamber long-axis CT reconstruction shows the normal appearance of a Sapien 3 device in the mitral position (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Two-chamber long-axis CT reconstruction shows the normal appearance of a Tendyne TMVR device (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200027&amp;id=fig24a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig24b" class="graphic" aria-label="Normal appearances of TMVR devices following implantation. (a) Two-chamber long-axis CT reconstruction shows the normal appearance of a Sapien 3 device in the mitral position (arrow). (b) Two-chamber long-axis CT reconstruction shows the normal appearance of a Tendyne TMVR device (arrow)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200027/asset/images/large/rg.2020200027.fig24b.jpeg" height="1418" width="1664" aria-labelledby="fig24b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 24b</span>. Normal appearances of TMVR devices following implantation. <b>(a)</b> Two-chamber long-axis CT reconstruction shows the normal appearance of a Sapien 3 device in the mitral position (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Two-chamber long-axis CT reconstruction shows the normal appearance of a Tendyne TMVR device (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200027&amp;id=fig24b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig25" class="graphic" aria-label="TMVR-induced LVOT obstruction. Three-chamber long-axis CT reconstructed image shows severe narrowing of the neo-LVOT (straight arrow) by the implanted TMVR device (curved arrow)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200027/asset/images/large/rg.2020200027.fig25.jpeg" height="1283" width="1800" aria-labelledby="fig25" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 25</span>. TMVR-induced LVOT obstruction. Three-chamber long-axis CT reconstructed image shows severe narrowing of the neo-LVOT (straight arrow) by the implanted TMVR device (curved arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200027&amp;id=fig25">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig26" class="graphic" aria-label="Pseudoaneurysm. Short-axis reconstructed CT image in a patient with a Caisson TMVR device (curved arrow) shows a 1.3 × 1.4-cm pseudoaneurysm with a narrow neck (*) located in the basal inferoseptum (straight arrow)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200027/asset/images/large/rg.2020200027.fig26.jpeg" height="1327" width="1700" aria-labelledby="fig26" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 26</span>. Pseudoaneurysm. Short-axis reconstructed CT image in a patient with a Caisson TMVR device (curved arrow) shows a 1.3 × 1.4-cm pseudoaneurysm with a narrow neck (*) located in the basal inferoseptum (straight arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200027&amp;id=fig26">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig27" class="graphic" aria-label="Malpositioned TMVR valve. Four-chamber long-axis reconstructed CT image shows an abnormally positioned TMVR device (arrow), which is predominantly located within the left atrium."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200027/asset/images/large/rg.2020200027.fig27.jpeg" height="1844" width="1700" aria-labelledby="fig27" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 27</span>. Malpositioned TMVR valve. Four-chamber long-axis reconstructed CT image shows an abnormally positioned TMVR device (arrow), which is predominantly located within the left atrium.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200027&amp;id=fig27">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div></section><section id="bibliography" role="doc-bibliography"><h2>References</h2><div role="list"><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">1.</div><div id="r1" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">Nkomo VT, Gardin JM, Skelton TN, Gottdiener JS, Scott CG, Enriquez-Sarano M. Burden of valvular heart diseases: a population-based study. <em>Lancet</em> 2006;368(9540):1005–1011.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-crossref"><a href="https://doi.org/10.1016/S0140-6736(06)69208-8">Crossref</a></div><div class="core-xlink-pubmed"><a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/16980116/">PubMed</a></div><div class="core-xlink-google-scholar"><a href="https://scholar.google.com/scholar_lookup?title=Burden+of+valvul